kxa-gdxf-5l0y,"The OCC should not have regulations related to climate change as they affect banks.  This is no different than banks not having regulations how their investments are affected by sunspots, animal evolution, shifting consumer preferences, or other specific external factors.  External factors always come into play into any decision, and singling out climate change as one that rises to the importance of requiring a policy appears to be purely political and not related to any relevant century-long event that affects investments on the relatively short term time horizon that banks lend money or make investment decisions on.  And although these regulations would initially apply to only banks of larger than $100 billion, as we all know, regulation creep seems to percolate downward into smaller banks who are ill equipped to deal with an unnecessary burden amongst all other other regulatory burdens that are placed on them.","The commenter argues against the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) implementing regulations related to climate change for banks. They compare climate change to other external factors like sunspots and consumer preferences, suggesting that singling out climate change is politically motivated rather than based on its relevance to short-term investment decisions. The commenter believes that such regulations are unnecessary and could lead to regulatory creep, eventually affecting smaller banks that are less equipped to handle additional regulatory burdens."
kxa-lnjk-b95u,"-----Original Message----- From: Robert Rutkowski <r_e_rutkowski@att.net> Sent: Friday, December 17, 2021 10:21 AM To: Publicaffairs <Publicaffairs3@occ.treas.gov> Cc: Keith Abouchar <keith.abouchar@mail.house.gov> Subject: [EXTERNAL]OCC Seeks Input on Climate Risk Management for Large Banks ***CAUTION***: External Email CAUTION: This email originated from outside of the organization. Do not click links or open attachments unless you recognize the sender and know the content is safe. ***CAUTION***: External Email Michael J. Hsu, Comptroller Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) Legislative and Regulatory Activities Division OCC Headquarters 400 7th Street, SW Washington, D.C. 20219 (202) 649-6800 E-mail: publicaffairs3@occ.treas.gov Re: OCC Seeks Input on Climate Risk Management for Large Banks Dear Acting Comptroller: The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) is applauded for seeking comment on this strong first draft of principles to guide large banks on how to manage the risk that climate change poses to their safety and soundness. This draft guidance for large banks represents a critical initial step in getting banks to manage and mitigate climate risks to their portfolios stemming from acute and chronic climate impacts, as well as the inevitable transition to a cleaner, more resilient economy. Importantly, the document explains how climate risk manifests across the traditional risk stripes considered by bank supervisors, and how banks should incorporate climate change into risk management, strategic planning, data collection and disclosure, and scenario analysis. The OCC, the Fed, the NCUA, and the FDIC should move forward quickly on detailed climate supervisory expectations for banks of all sizes. As an FDIC Board member also move expeditiously to advance climate guidance for that agency as well. Yours sincerely,
Robert E. Rutkowski cc: Legislative Correspondence Team Longworth House Office Building Washington DC 20515 keith.abouchar@mail.house.gov 2527 Faxon Court Topeka, Kansas 66605-2086 P/F: 1 785 379-9671 E-mail: r_e_rutkowski@att.net ***CAUTION***: External Email CAUTION: This email originated from outside the organization. Do not click links or open attachments unless you recognize the sender and know the content is safe. ***CAUTION***: External Email","Robert Rutkowski commends the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) for its draft guidance on climate risk management for large banks. He views this as a crucial first step in helping banks manage and mitigate risks associated with climate change, including both acute and chronic impacts, as well as the transition to a cleaner economy. Rutkowski highlights the importance of integrating climate risk into traditional risk management, strategic planning, data collection, disclosure, and scenario analysis. He urges the OCC, along with the Federal Reserve, National Credit Union Administration (NCUA), and Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC), to quickly establish detailed climate supervisory expectations for banks of all sizes. Additionally, he encourages the FDIC to advance its own climate guidance promptly."
kxe-4g4t-gqnz,"Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks is not a bad beginning for a high-level principles document, but given the magnitude of the risks from climate change and the speed with which it is unfolding, much more detailed and proscriptive regulations are needed with urgency.  As a public citizen seeking to prepare for retirement, I find that banks and brokers are almost uniformly uninformed about the true nature and size of the threat from climate change.  Insurance instruments can deflect the risk but the Federal government is the insurer of last resort and young taxpayers will bear all the burden of paying for disaster recovery when the banks and insurers fail.  Banks of all sizes should be required to base their risk assessments on named scientific panels, bodies, and databases such as climatecentral.org‚Äôs surging seas floodmap.  FEMA‚Äôs floodmaps are drawn subject to input from biased entities such as local governemnt officials who have an interest in marketing their cities and counties.  That is why purely scientific databases should be the basis for risk assessments and decision-making.  In fact it would be best if regulatory bodies such as the FEC and OCC had climate scientists on staff participating in the oversight and evaluation of banks‚Äô climate-related risk management policies.  As an example, I‚Äôll wager that the banks and investors who have extended loans to the Kentucky candle factory that blew down in a tornado last week had no inkling that climate change substantially multiplies the number and size of tornadoes that will hit the southeastern US to the point where such occurences will be routine.  Banks have data scientists on staff already.  They need climate scientists and ecologists.","The comment critiques the ""Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks"" as insufficient given the urgent and significant risks posed by climate change. The commenter argues for more detailed and prescriptive regulations, emphasizing that banks and brokers lack awareness of climate threats. They highlight the role of the Federal government as the insurer of last resort, burdening young taxpayers with disaster recovery costs. The comment suggests that banks should base risk assessments on scientific data from sources like climatecentral.org, rather than biased inputs like FEMA's floodmaps. It advocates for regulatory bodies to include climate scientists in oversight roles, citing a recent tornado in Kentucky as an example of underestimated climate risks. The commenter calls for banks to employ climate scientists and ecologists alongside data scientists."
ky7-rsyf-ikno,Seems like nothing more than a bold attempt to force banks to select only clients that supposedly do not contribute to climate change. A back doorway to deny oil/gas/coal and other companies access to loans. I oppose this regulation.,"The comment criticizes a policy proposal as an attempt to pressure banks into choosing clients based on their environmental impact, specifically targeting those involved in oil, gas, and coal industries. The commenter perceives this as a strategy to restrict these companies' access to loans and expresses opposition to the regulation."
kxu-km0l-0ndk,"Carbon Quotient‚Ñ¢ ‚Äì how to create accountability for net zero across the investment value chain Getting to net zero by 2050 is like an endurance auto race across the desert where drivers must traverse dunes, mud, rocks, and barren sand seas. Fans and racers each need a global positioning system (GPS) to gauge the relative position of the competitors and avoid losing their way on an off-road course with no markers. This paper introduces Carbon Quotient (CQ) analytics, a revolutionary open-source application of well-established accounting concepts to measure, manage and report climate-related financial risk. CQ analytics provide a much-needed GPS to guide decision-making on capital allocation and hold corporations and financial institutions accountable for measurable progress toward net zero over time. ¬© Charles Greg Rogers 2021 (TX 9-005-781). All rights reserved. Carbon Quotient and CQ are trademarks of C.G. Rogers & Co., LLC.
