It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The commenter expresses gratitude to Comptroller Hsu for addressing climate change in relation to banks. They emphasize the importance of banks considering the long-term effects of climate change rather than focusing solely on immediate profits from the fossil fuel industry. The commenter argues that protecting the environment is crucial for both public and financial health. They urge the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) to use its authority to issue strong guidance to banks on managing climate risk, ensure protection against unsafe banking practices, and require banks to implement remedies when necessary. The overall message is a call for proactive measures to minimize climate risk for the benefit of both the public and the banking sector."
kyl-scl0-v79b,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. 
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. 
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, as stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they:
Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business;
Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available;
Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 
And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too.
It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.  We ALL have to protect this planet!","The comment thanks Comptroller Hsu for addressing climate change in banking, highlighting the contradiction between banks' public commitments to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and their continued investments in fossil fuels. It argues that these investments exacerbate climate change, posing risks to the financial system, marginalized communities, and the planet. The commenter urges regulators to prevent banks from making short-term decisions that threaten the economy and communities. They support the proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public climate commitments. The commenter emphasizes the need for the OCC to ensure banks' actions align with their net-zero carbon commitments and to incorporate climate risk management into supervisory ratings. They call for strong guidance from the OCC to minimize climate risk and protect against unsafe banking practices, stressing the urgency of collective action to protect the planet."
