kyn-soiq-qte4,"Developing Climate Risk Assessment Regulations or Climate Risk Regulatory Guidance is a daunting task for many reasons. To begin with, Climate Risk needs to be clearly defined. Many articles and studies on Climate Risk focus on the future and speculate on widely differing scenarios about how Climate Change will affect Climate Risk. In my opinion, commingling Climate Risk with Climate Change is a mistake at this time. The extent and effects of Climate Change remain the subject of a continuing debate about both the degree of climate change, the rate of climate change, and the effects of Climate Change.
When developing possible guidance and potential regulations pertaining to Climate Risk why not start with a ‚Äúfirst generation‚Äù basic Climate Risk model and then build upon that model with time and experience?
What do I mean by a basic Climate Risk model? What I suggest is that the first generation of Climate Risk Assessments should be based on Climate Risk as it exists today without the controversy surrounding Climate Change speculation. 
This approach has many advantages. First, as with any new regulation, the first generation of Climate Risk Assessment Models will be controversial. Adopting a Climate Risk Model that is based on current-day conditions reduces the speculation and controversy involved when incorporating Climate Change considerations.
Second, there already exists data that measure climate exposure for many natural hazards, including flooding, hurricanes, earthquakes, drought, severe cold, and more than a dozen other climate-related phenomena that are currently a real and immediate threat to banks and the communities they serve.
Third, by focusing on imminent climate-related threats, climate risk assessments are not only likely to be more accurate but are more likely to attract more support because it‚Äôs easier to perceive and appreciate a threat that currently exists and could happen any day, rather than a threat that may be decades away.
How quickly could such a Climate Risk Assessment Model be developed? The answer is such a model already is available. Using data generated by at least 8 federal agencies GeoDataVision has adapted that data for banking purposes so that risk ratings in that data can be assigned to any bank asset, facility, loan or collateral location, etc. If anyone from the OCC is interested in reviewing the maps and risk ratings within the model, I would be pleased to provide a demonstration. We have written an article for publication regarding the model and are awaiting the approval process. As soon as that article is published (expected the first week of February) we will provide a copy to the OCC. Len Suzio","The comment addresses the challenges of developing Climate Risk Assessment Regulations, emphasizing the need to clearly define Climate Risk separately from Climate Change. The author argues against conflating Climate Risk with Climate Change due to ongoing debates about the latter's extent and effects. They propose starting with a ""first generation"" Climate Risk model based on current conditions, which would reduce speculation and controversy. This model would utilize existing data on natural hazards like flooding and hurricanes, making assessments more accurate and garnering more support by focusing on immediate threats. The author claims such a model already exists, adapted by GeoDataVision using federal data for banking purposes, and offers to demonstrate it to the OCC. An article on the model is pending publication."
