kzd-6cz9-94vu,"Comptroller Hsu,  I appreciate your effort but don't envy you in the complications of the task you are facing. Clearly, climate change will effect many aspects of our lives going into the future. Converting from hydrocarbons to green energy sources is paramount. We use petrochemicals in many ways (including lubricants, plastics, rubber, and even cosmetics); but we don't want to continue burning it up into the atmosphere. With the news of a large Antarctic ice shelf calving and melting such that the ocean level is projected to rise 1 to 3 feet. The ice sheets that the ice shelf was holding back is projected to add another 3 to 6 feet in sea level rise. Clearly many cities and towns along the coastline are poised to become the Venice of the US. One should think that financing projects that are untenable to maintain is a risk not worth taking. But what happens when the risk area is an entire city (like Miami)? We don't want the Federal government to be the backstop for bad financial decisions (as in the 2008 fiasco). My suggestion is that a table utilizing land elevations versus projected sea rise be used to limit the terms of any financial loan being proposed and granted in low lying areas. If we project sea levels to rise 1 to 3 feet in the next 10 years and the project is on coastal land 1.5 feet above current sea level, then no loan with a term longer than 10 years should ever be allowed. Going forward the term of any new loan should decrease based on the current sea level rise. A set table (or equation) for all to follow will provide clarity to the risk management sought. FEMA is the vehicle that will tap into scarce public funds due to bad financial decisions as each of the accelerating instances caused by climate change occur. It seems wise to also put term limits on loans for petrochemical projects as we try to ween our energy economy off of fossil fuels for the next critical decades. Coming up with some standard of term limiting loans would be the simplest and cleanest way to address the risk problem we all face. Thank you for your consideration. John Saour","The comment addresses Comptroller Hsu, expressing appreciation for efforts in tackling climate change issues. The commenter emphasizes the importance of transitioning from hydrocarbons to green energy, noting the extensive use of petrochemicals and the environmental impact of burning them. Highlighting the recent Antarctic ice shelf calving, the commenter warns of significant sea level rise, which threatens coastal cities. They argue against financing projects in vulnerable areas, suggesting that loans for such projects should be limited based on projected sea level rise. The commenter proposes a standardized table or equation to guide loan terms, ensuring financial decisions account for climate risks. They also recommend term limits on loans for petrochemical projects to support the transition to renewable energy. The comment concludes by urging consideration of these measures to manage climate-related financial risks effectively."
