I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The comment emphasizes the need for regulatory support to aid grassroots organizers in influencing banks and asset managers to shift investments away from fossil fuels. The commenter thanks Comptroller Hsu for addressing climate change in banking, highlighting the contradiction between banks' public commitments to climate action and their continued investments in fossil fuels. This investment is seen as exacerbating climate change, which threatens the financial system, marginalized communities, and the planet. The commenter supports proposed guidance urging banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public climate commitments. They advocate for banks' climate risk management to influence supervisory ratings and call for the OCC to enforce strong guidance to ensure banks' actions align with their zero carbon emissions commitments, protecting against unsafe practices and requiring remedies where necessary."
kze-n9x2-kdll,"4 February 2022 To: Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) Re: Docket ID OCC-2021-0023: Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks The United Nations Environment Programme - Finance Initiative (UNEP FI) is a strategic public- private partnership between the UN and over 400 global financial institutions. It has established some of the most important sustainability-oriented frameworks within the finance industry, including the Principles for Responsible Investment, the Principles for Sustainable Insurance and the Principles for Responsible Banking. It also convenes leading net zero alliances of banks, insurers and asset owners which form part of the Glasgow Financial Alliance for Net-Zero. Since the issuance of the initial TCFD disclosure guidance, UNEP FI has led pilot programmes for over 100 banks, insurers and institutional investors on climate risk and TCFD disclosures. These programs have convened financial institutions, supervisors, and climate experts with a view to improving climate disclosure and climate risk management across the financial sector. Overview UNEP FI welcomes the publication of the OCC‚Äôs Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks. This document provides actionable guidance to both financial institutions and financial supervisors. Within this document, we particularly welcome the following: ‚Ä¢ Continued acknowledgement that climate risks are financial risks and that additional guidance is required within the financial sector for their management ‚Ä¢ Recognition that climate change poses capital, liquidity, credit, legal/compliance, operational, and other risks ‚Ä¢ Principles for firms to evaluate their climate risks ‚Ä¢ A set of operational areas to consider in managing climate risks: governance, policies, procedures, and limits, strategic planning, risk management, data, risk management, and reporting, and scenario analysis ‚Ä¢ Guidance to consider multiple time horizons and different scenarios in assessing the preparedness of an institution to face climate-related financial risks ‚Ä¢ Specific guidance on approaches for the monitoring and reporting of climate-related financial risks by financial institutions We have a few reflections and recommendations on the principles that we believe would be helpful to share. In this response, we have addressed the associated consultation questions accompanying this evaluation process.
Questions Applicability 1. Are there additional categories of banks (i.e., based on asset size, location, business model) to which these principles should apply? UNEP FI believes the principles articulated by the OCC are widely applicable to banks of all sizes. At present, they only apply to banks with over 100 billion dollars in total assets. While regulatory reporting or assessment requirements may vary by size and systemic importance of the institution, climate risks do not discriminate. Smaller banks are not immune to climate risks and may even be more susceptible if they are particularly concentrated in vulnerable sectors or geographies. Other supervisors such as the PRA in the UK have espoused similar principles but have not limited their scope by bank size. They instead require that regulated firms adopt a proportionate approach to managing those climate risks to which they are exposed, whilst also providing guidance as to what this might look like in practice. Tailoring 2. How could future guidance assist a bank in developing its climate-related financial risk management practices commensurate to its size, complexity, risk profile, and scope of operations? Though UNEP FI‚Äôs work across multiple geographies, a constant request from financial institutions is to see examples of good practices in the diverse areas of climate risk management. Case studies on good practice can be a particularly useful resource for institutions as evidenced by the CDSB‚Äôs TCFD Good Practice Handbook and the IIF and UNEP FI‚Äôs TCFD Report Playbook. In the future, supervisors can also provide more detailed and actionable guidance through reports on the application of their principles. Firms in the Eurozone and UK have, in particular, found the supervisory review reports of the ECB and PRA useful in implementing their climate risk expectations. The work the NGFS has developed in conjunction with its members has also proved useful. When considering examples for inclusion, it is valuable to offer a diversity of examples that are applicable to banks of different sizes, geographies, risk profiles, and complexity. Guidance from regulator-sponsored industry forums has additionally provided useful risk management insights to different firm-types. In the UK for example, the PRA and the FCA co-chair the Climate Financial Risk Forum (‚ÄòCFRF‚Äô) whose members are drawn from industry. The CFRF has been successful in developing a significant body of practical industry guidance with regards to climate risk management covering diverse topics such as risk appetite statements, data, tools and scenario analysis. UNEP FI‚Äôs banking members have found that outreach by regulators has been an effective way for firms to better understand regulatory expectations and regulators to better appreciate current industry practices and challenges. General 3. What challenges do banks face in incorporating these principles into their risk management systems? How should the OCC further engage with banks to understand those challenges? The challenges faced by firms many vary based on the nature of their exposures and the level of maturity in their climate risk program, but some common challenges can be identified. These include: 2
‚Ä¢ Quantification of climate risks in both risk management and reporting. This challenge relates to a need to develop suitable models for the quantification, a need for stakeholders to understand and trust the outputs, and a need to assimilate those outputs into existing decision-making processes. ‚Ä¢ Data limitations. This challenge pertains both to the availability of credible emissions data (especially for small and medium enterprise clients) for transition risk assessments as well as granular data on physical risks for different geographies. The identification of client legal risks is another area where data may be a limiting factor. ‚Ä¢ Updating existing business practices. This challenge concerns the fact that even when analysis is conducted for TCFD reporting or to meet regulatory requirements, there is no guarantee that it is used to shape future strategy or decision-making. Processes and procedures around underwriting and origination as well as risk limits and thresholds all need to be updated to consider climate risks. As noted in the prior response, the OCC can help firms overcome these challenges through reports that offer example-based guidance on good practices and engagement with industry initiatives dedicated to tackling these challenges. UNEP FI believes that increased regulatory demands for climate disclosure have enhanced the quality of climate-related financial disclosures overall and scenario analysis in particular. Thoughtful regulatory assessments with compliance consequences and capital adequacy assessments can further advance the integration of climate risk management into firms‚Äô existing operations. Current Risk Management Practices UNEP FI believes that these questions can be best answered directly by banks responding to this consultation. However, there are a few points that may be useful to briefly mention along with some resources that explore these topics in greater detail. 4. What specific tools or strategies have banks used to successfully incorporate climate-related financial risks into their risk management frameworks? In 2021, UNEP FI released a report on the landscape of climate risk tools that provides an overview on the features of more than 3 dozen physical and transition risk tools. In March of 2022, a supplement to this report will be released with over a dozen case studies from institutions that have piloted some of the latest commercially available tools. 5. How do banks determine when climate-related financial risks are material and warrant greater than routine attention by the board and management? Materiality has been a challenging term to define, but it is worth considering the TCFD secretariat‚Äôs perspective: ‚Äúcompanies should determine materiality for climate-related issues consistent with how they determine the materiality of other information included in their financial filings.‚Äù Complicating this approach may be the long-term and non-traditional nature of climate risks. In addition, considerations of ‚Äúdouble materiality‚Äù are increasingly important, assessing not only climate risks faced by the firm, but risks that the firm‚Äôs activities pose to the climate. UNEP FI believes that heatmapping can be an important tool for initial assessment of the materiality of climate risks. In Beyond the Horizon, UNEP FI and its members developed a transition risk heatmap for a number of sectors and did likewise for physical risks in Charting a New Climate. 3
6. What time horizon do banks consider relevant when identifying and assessing the materiality of climate-related financial risks? UNEP FI considers risk assessment over a variety of different time horizons critical to evaluating a firm‚Äôs climate risks. While most strategic planning within financial institutions takes place within a 3-5 year time horizon, climate risk demands a wider range of assessment windows. Other organizations and initiatives, such as the investor-led Climate Action 100+, have defined specific horizons for short-term, medium-term, and long-term in ways that might be helpful for the OCC to consider. An example of similar action by a regulator comes from the European Banking Authority, which suggested that firms extend their strategic planning to at least 10 years. 7. What, if any, specific products, practices, and strategies‚Äìfor example, insurance or derivatives contracts or other capital market instruments‚Äìdo banks use to hedge, transfer, or mitigate climate-related financial risks? Institutions have pursued diverse strategies to mitigate their climate risks including and in addition to the ones mentioned in the question. Some firms have developed exclusion lists or updated underwriting criteria to reduce potential climate risks. Others have set limits and targets on certain sectors or geographies. 8. What, if any, climate-related financial products or services‚Äìfor example, ‚Äúgreen bonds,‚Äù derivatives, dedicated investment funds, or other instruments that take climate-related considerations into account‚Äìdo banks offer to clients and customers?4 What risks, if any, do these products or services pose? The ESG investing space has grown massively in the last few years. Similarly, demand for green projects has also grown and many firms are experimenting with new green products. The Climate Bonds Initiative has been a thought leader on the origination and development of these new products. Some institutions have gotten actively involved in carbon credit markets as well. With the rise in enthusiasm for ESG finance, scrutiny must be applied by supervisors to ensure claims of environmental impact are not just greenwash and to monitor the potential creation of a green asset bubble. 9. How do banks currently consider the impacts of climate-related financial risk mitigation strategies and financial products on households and communities, specifically LMI and other disadvantaged communities? One of the many injustices of climate change is its disproportionate impact on the least fortunate. This holds true on a national as well as global level when considering the negative health effects of fossil fuel combustion or the consequences of worsening extreme events. Climate finance must be careful not to exacerbate the plight of society‚Äôs most vulnerable members in an effort to manage risk. Risk management should consider the needs of adaptation finance and community investment. This complex issue will likely require government or international intervention to prevent disinvestment under the guise of risk mitigation. At present, some banks are considering the climate impacts on local communities and supporting investment in climate-resilient infrastructure. Banks have also provided adaptation finance to municipalities and other local governments. 4
Data, Disclosures, and Reporting 10. What, if any, specific climate-related data, metrics, tools, and models from borrowers and other counterparties do banks need to identify, measure, monitor, and control their own climate-related financial risks? How do banks currently obtain this information? What gaps and other concerns are there with respect to these data, metrics, tools, or models? As mentioned previously, UNEP FI‚Äôs 2021 Landscape Report provides details on climate risk tools. It also covers a variety of data providers. In terms of specific data and metrics, UNEP FI‚Äôs recent paper: A Good Practice Guide to Stress Testing contains a data section that elaborates the data requirements for physical and transition risk assessments. From a regulatory perspective, in 2021 the NGFS released a report on bridging data gaps, which highlights progress and remaining challenges in obtaining the necessary data for climate risk assessments. These publications contain common themes regarding banks‚Äô climate data needs. Banks will need to work with clients, public data sources, and potentially commercial data providers to obtain the required data. Key considerations for climate data include: ‚Ä¢ Transition risk o Asset-level emissions data o Client transition plans o Granular transition pathways with relevant macroeconomic factors (e.g. energy demand, carbon price) o Legal proceedings against clients ‚Ä¢ Physical risk o Multi-hazard risk forecasts for specific areas o Geolocation of assets o Resiliency plans for assets 11. How could existing regulatory reporting requirements be augmented to better capture banks‚Äô exposure to climate-related financial risks? COP 26 saw the announcement of the International Sustainability Standards Board (ISSB), which aims to consolidate the work of a number of sustainability initiatives into a coherent standard. In late 2021, the TCFD secretariat released consultations on transition plans, disclosure metrics, and portfolio alignment methodologies. Alignment around both disclosure standards and on good practices for climate risk management is important for financial sector actors. Supervisors can continue to augment their reporting requirements by considering how their requirements align with and build on the work of the ISSB and TCFD. A helpful example of regulatory standards that build on the common TCFD framework comes from the EBA‚Äôs Final draft implementing technical standards on prudential disclosures on ESG risks. Scenario Analysis 12. Scenario analysis is an important component of climate risk management that requires assumptions about plausible future states of the world. How do banks use climate scenario models, analysis, or tools and what challenges do they face? Banks are increasingly conducting climate scenario analysis for a variety of purposes. Use cases include regulatory assessments: mandated climate disclosures (and TCFD reporting) and climate stress tests, 5
development of a climate strategy, opportunity identification, client engagement, net-zero alignment and more traditional risk management: including updating underwriting criteria and setting climate-informed limits and targets. In conjunction with the Center for International Climate Research (CICERO), UNEP FI has published a guide on the use of integrated assessment models (IAMs) for financial practitioners entitled Pathways to Paris. With Oliver Wyman, UNEP FI also built a transition risk assessment tool that incorporates a variety of NGFS scenarios and their relative impacts on different sectors and geographies. UNEP FI will also be publishing two papers on scenario analysis in Q2 2022 for financial practitioners. The NGFS has developed a dedicated resource for those looking to use both their physical and transition risk scenarios that has proven useful to many institutions. Other commercial and non-commercial organizations are also working on similar scenario databases and tools. Common challenges that banks face when conducting climate scenario analysis include: ‚Ä¢ Lacking institutional knowledge about important climate scenario assumptions and how to interpret and apply results ‚Ä¢ Translating climate-related factors into financial risk drivers ‚Ä¢ Producing analysis that is relevant on the timeframes typically used to set bank strategy ‚Ä¢ Having adequate coverage of certain sectors and regions (non-energy sectors and non-OECD regions tend to have less data) 13. What factors are most salient for the OCC to consider when designing and executing scenario analysis exercises? As 1.5Àö C has become a global climate goal, it would be helpful to make an explicit recommendation that scenario analysis include scenarios aligned to this temperature outcome. As previously stated, risk assessment over a variety of different time horizons is necessary in evaluating a firm‚Äôs climate risks. Climate scenario analysis should use scenarios and generate outputs with relevance over multiple time horizons. Other considerations include: ‚Ä¢ Scenarios considering the combined impacts of both physical and transition risks ‚Ä¢ Scenarios with varying degrees of economic severity ‚Ä¢ Transition scenarios with abrupt policy shifts, economic disruptions, and price volatility ‚Ä¢ Physical scenarios with impacts on supply chains, and the incorporation of tail risks and tipping points Should the OCC have any questions about this response, UNEP FI would be delighted to discuss our perspectives further or answer any related comments or questions. Sincerely, Eric Usher Head, UNEP-FI 6","The United Nations Environment Programme - Finance Initiative (UNEP FI) supports the OCC's Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks, emphasizing the need for guidance on managing climate risks, which are financial risks. UNEP FI suggests that these principles should apply to banks of all sizes, not just those with over $100 billion in assets, as climate risks affect all institutions. They recommend providing examples of good practices and detailed guidance to help banks develop climate risk management practices. Challenges include quantifying climate risks, data limitations, and updating business practices. UNEP FI highlights the importance of regulatory engagement and reports to overcome these challenges. They also discuss the need for diverse strategies to mitigate climate risks, the importance of considering impacts on disadvantaged communities, and the necessity of robust data and reporting standards. Scenario analysis is crucial, and UNEP FI suggests including scenarios aligned with the 1.5¬∞C global climate goal. They offer to discuss their perspectives further with the OCC."
kze-u73r-xtwi,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. Climate change is the biggest threat to the continuation of human society as we have known it and we must act strongly to stabilize our climate. Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The comment addresses Comptroller Hsu, expressing gratitude for addressing climate change in relation to banks. It highlights climate change as a major threat and criticizes banks for investing in fossil fuels despite public commitments to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. The comment argues that banks' investments exacerbate climate change, risking the financial system, marginalized communities, and the planet. It urges regulators to prevent banks from making short-term decisions that endanger the economy and communities. The commenter supports proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate change, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public commitments. They advocate for banks' climate risk management to influence supervisory ratings and call for the OCC to enforce strong guidance and remedies to ensure banks' actions align with their zero carbon emission commitments."
kze-u786-lton,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. I am not pleased that Chase bought my mortgage from my small lender when I refinanced last year. But....I hope that my position as a customer of the worst climate bank on the planet holds a little weight. I didn't even have a choice and would never have picked Chase to get a dime of my money. So just know that this isn't about consumer choice. Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
