kze-u7wr-fovy,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities. It is not enough to ask individuals to change their behavior, we need to hold the financial community responsible for their behavior.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.","The comment addresses Comptroller Hsu, expressing gratitude for addressing climate change in relation to banks. It criticizes banks for publicly claiming to address climate change while investing heavily in fossil fuel companies, which exacerbates climate change and endangers the financial system, marginalized communities, and the planet. The commenter urges regulators to prevent banks from making short-term decisions that threaten the economy and communities, emphasizing the need for financial institutions to be held accountable. The commenter supports the proposed guidance for banks, which includes integrating climate risk management at all business levels, planning for long-term climate change, updating models with new data, defining climate risk exposures and metrics, and ensuring internal strategies align with public climate commitments."
kze-u7yq-v3tr,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
