kze-ujgd-k4vl,"I am a resident of California and a Climate Activist. I have two adult children and many nieces and nephews who are starting families. For their sakes we need to stop relying of fossil fuels. As we get more serious about converting to alternate power for vehicles drilling for oil does not make fiscal sense as demand goes down. The financial risk for banks funding new fossil fuel project is much riskier than currently implemented.
I am calling on you to factor in the risk of any new funding for the banks funding these projects. I support the following recommendations for banks: 1. Embed climate-related risk management at all levels of business; 2. Plan for long-term climate change and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of potential climate-related risk exposures and metrics to set limits; 4. Ensure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public commitments regarding climate change.
The OCC must ensure that the banks' actions are consistent with their commitments to reduce their carbon emissions to net zero. Banks' management of climate risk should also factor into their supervisory ratings. The best thing for the public and the banks themselves is to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC should use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe banking practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The commenter, a California resident and climate activist, urges a shift away from fossil fuels, emphasizing the need for alternative energy sources as demand for oil decreases. They highlight the financial risks for banks funding new fossil fuel projects and call for the integration of climate-related risk management in banking. The commenter supports recommendations for banks to embed climate risk management, plan for long-term climate change, develop clear risk definitions, and align internal strategies with public climate commitments. They urge the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) to ensure banks' actions align with their net-zero carbon emission commitments and to incorporate climate risk management into supervisory ratings. The commenter advocates for the OCC to issue strong guidance to banks on climate risk and enforce remedies for unsafe practices."
kze-uvup-ng99,"It is long past time to take climate change, and the more and more obvious effects on our world, into account in business decisions. The fossil fuel industry should be well on its way to transitioning to clean energy. Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.
I look forward to your actions to ensure the impacts of climate change are limited and finally eliminated!
Sincerely, Margaret Lang","The comment emphasizes the urgent need for businesses, particularly banks, to address climate change in their decision-making processes. The fossil fuel industry should transition to clean energy, and banks must stop financing fossil fuel companies, as their investments contribute to climate change, risking the financial system and vulnerable communities. The commenter supports proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public climate commitments. The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) should ensure banks' actions align with their zero carbon emissions commitments and factor climate risk management into supervisory ratings. The OCC is urged to issue strong guidance to protect against unsafe banking practices and require remedies where necessary. The commenter looks forward to actions that limit and eliminate climate change impacts."
kze-uq9f-v308,"I'm writing to thank you for addressing the issue of climate change and banks. This action is important and long-overdue. While banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, the truth is that they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system and our planet at risk,  disproportionately endangering people of color and low-income communities. 
This issue is personal to me, as climate change has already affected my family and my community. Members of my family live along the Mississippi River, where repeated ""100 year"" floods have directly affected them and their livelihoods. My elderly aunt and uncle live in Quincy, CA and were evacuated for weeks last year due to wildfires; two friends of mine lost everything in the Paradise fire; I have numerous additional friends and work colleagues who lost their homes to wildfires in other locations in California and Colorado over the past four years. A year and a half ago, the entire sky above my home was the color of blood in the middle of the day, and we spent weeks inside because the air was toxic from ash and smoke. Perhaps most importantly, I have a son who will be younger than I am today in 2050 -- a time horizon that is unfortunately much longer than that on which any of the banks you regulate operates.
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The comment expresses gratitude for addressing climate change in banking, highlighting the discrepancy between banks' public commitments and their continued investments in fossil fuels. The commenter emphasizes the personal impact of climate change, citing family and friends affected by floods and wildfires. They urge regulators to push banks to incorporate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate change, and ensure internal strategies align with public commitments. The commenter supports the proposed guidance for banks to manage climate risks and urges the OCC to enforce strong guidance and require banks to act responsibly to minimize climate risk."
kze-wy2c-pwpt,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. 
