Thank you for your consideration.","The comment addresses Comptroller Hsu, urging action on climate change and banks' roles in it. It criticizes banks for investing in high-emission technologies, contributing to climate change, which threatens agricultural and financial systems. The commenter supports proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, phase out carbon-intensive investments, and increase low-emission alternatives. They advocate for long-term climate planning, updating models with new data, and defining climate risk exposures with metrics. The comment emphasizes that banks' climate risk management should influence supervisory ratings and calls for the OCC to enforce strong guidance, protect against unsafe practices, and require banks to act on climate risks. The commenter stresses the urgency for both public and banks to minimize climate risk."
kzf-mh9t-yp8i,"Michael J. Hsu Acting Comptroller of the Currency 400 7th St. SW Washington, DC 20219 RE: Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks Dear Acting Comptroller Hsu, Thank you for the opportunity to comment on the O␀ce of the Comptroller of the Currency‚Äôs (OCC) Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks. Evergreen Action is a national non-profit leading the fight to put bold climate action at the top of America's agenda, implement an all-out mobilization to defeat climate change and create millions of jobs in a clean energy economy. Evergreen Action commends the OCC for issuing draft principles on how large banks should incorporate climate-related threats into their operations. Climate-related risks, including various physical and transition risks, pose a grave threat to the safety and soundness of individual banks and the financial system. These draft principles are a historic step in the right direction to protect working families from the threat of a climate-fueled financial crash ‚Äì and as such, we strongly encourage the OCC to implement this strong guidance. Evergreen Action is particularly supportive of the following recommendations in the draft guidance: 1. Banks should incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business, including policies, planning procedures, and limits; 2. Banks must plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as risks evolve and additional data becomes available; 3. It is crucial that banks ensure their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments. As well as expressing our broad support for the OCC‚Äôs draft principles, Evergreen Action would like to o␀er the following feedback. (Kindly note that we were also pleased to sign a letter, submitted by our colleagues at Public Citizen, that further expands upon these remarks.) Aligning Internal Strategies & Public Climate-Related Commitments: We commend the OCC‚Äôs draft guidance that recommends that any ‚Äúpublic statements about their banks‚Äô climate-related strategies and commitments are consistent with their internal
strategies and risk appetite statements‚Äù (p.3). This draft guidance appropriately holds banks accountable for their climate commitments and cracks down on greenwashing. This guidance is particularly relevant when discussing the recent commitments of large banks to create and execute net-zero transition plans. Last year, nine US banks, including Wells Fargo, Morgan Stanley, Citigroup, Bank of America, and JPMorgan Chase, made net-zero emissions commitments as members of the Net-Zero Banking Alliance (NZBA). Yet many of these banks are also the biggest bankers of the 100 top fossil fuel expansion companies over the last half decade, and many continue to finance new greenhouse-gas related activities ‚Äì actions that fly in the face of goals to limit global temperature rise to 1.5 degrees Celsius. Now, the OCC should amend its draft guidance to say that banks committing to net-zero by 2050 transition plans should develop and implement credible internal strategies. These strategies must align with the demands of climate science, meet the imperatives of safety and soundness, and have measurable short and medium-term milestones, like a 50% reduction in financed emissions by 2030. As pointed out in the Public Citizen letter co-signed by Evergreen Action, measurable milestones are not only necessary for accountability, but also help avoid a ‚Äúfire sale from banks trying to meet their commitments at the last minute‚Äù ‚Äì in turn, a matter of safety and soundness. Fair access to financial services: The OCC‚Äôs draft guidance applies to large banks with $100B or more in consolidated assets. Yet, as pointed out in a letter drafted by Public Citizen and co-signed by Evergreen Action, more than 80% of banks supervised by the OCC are community banks that are particularly vulnerable to climate change. Community banks typically serve certain areas and cannot easily shift locations without impacting local communities. At minimum, the OCC should acknowledge risks to community banks and highlight that the best risk-management measure for community banks is to reduce climate impacts through slashing emissions. You may find further recommendations related to aligning public climate commitments and internal strategies, o␀sets, and fair access to financial services in the Public Citizen group letter, which we have co-signed. Thank you for your consideration and work on this e␀ort. Sincerely, Evergreen Action PO Box 21961, Seattle WA 98111","Evergreen Action, a national non-profit focused on climate action, commends the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) for its draft principles on climate-related financial risk management for large banks. They emphasize the importance of integrating climate risk management into all business levels, planning for long-term climate change, and ensuring internal strategies align with public climate commitments to prevent greenwashing. Evergreen Action supports the OCC's guidance, particularly in holding banks accountable for their climate commitments, and suggests that banks should develop credible strategies with measurable milestones, such as a 50% reduction in financed emissions by 2030. They also highlight the vulnerability of community banks to climate change and suggest that the OCC should address these risks. Evergreen Action co-signed a letter with Public Citizen, offering further recommendations on aligning public commitments with internal strategies and ensuring fair access to financial services."
