kzh-jjr6-yo8o,"Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks Introduction The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) has identified the effects of climate change and the transition to a low carbon economy as presenting emerging risks to banks1 and the financial system.2 Banks are likely to be affected by both the physical risks and transition risks associated with climate change (referred to in these draft principles as climate-related financial risks). Physical risks refer to the harm to people and property arising from acute, climate-related events, such as hurricanes, wildfires, floods, and heatwaves, and chronic shifts in climate, including higher average temperatures, changes in precipitation patterns, sea level rise, and ocean acidification. Transition risks refer to stresses to certain banks or sectors arising from the shifts in policy, consumer and business sentiment, or technologies associated with the changes necessary to limit climate change. Weaknesses in how banks identify, measure, monitor, and control the potential physical and transition risks associated with a changing climate could adversely affect a bank‚Äôs safety and soundness, as well as the overall financial system. Adverse effects could include potentially disproportionate impact on the financially vulnerable, including low- to moderate-income (LMI) and other disadvantaged households and communities.3 Many banks are considering these risks and would benefit from additional guidance as they develop capabilities, deploy resources, and make necessary investments to address climate-related financial risks. These draft principles provide a high-level framework for the safe and sound management of exposures to climate-related financial risks, consistent with the existing risk management framework described in existing OCC rules and guidance. The principles are intended to support efforts by banks to focus on key aspects of climate risk management. The principles will help bank management make progress toward answering key questions on exposures and incorporating climate-related financial risks into banks‚Äô risk management frameworks. Although all banks, regardless of size, may have material exposures to climate-related financial risks, these draft principles are targeted at the largest banks, those with over $100 billion in total 1 In this issuance, the term ‚Äúbank‚Äù refers collectively to national banks, Federal savings associations, and Federal branches or agencies of foreign banking organizations. 2 See e.g. Semiannual Risk Perspective at pp. 2-4 (Fall 2021), available at https://www.occ.treas.gov/publications- and-resources/publications/semiannual-risk-perspective/files/pub-semiannual-risk-perspective-fall-2021.pdf. For additional background, see generally Report on Climate-Related Financial Risk, Financial Stability Oversight Council (Oct. 21, 2021) (FSOC Climate Report). 3 For further information, see Staff Reports, Federal Reserve Bank of New York, Understanding the Linkages between Climate Change and Inequality in the United States, No. 991 (November 2021), available at https://www.newyorkfed.org/research/staff_reports/sr991.html.
consolidated assets. The OCC is inviting public feedback on the principles for 60 days, until February 14, 2022. The OCC plans to elaborate on these principles in subsequent guidance that would distinguish roles and responsibilities of boards of directors (boards) and management, incorporate the feedback received on the principles, and consider lessons learned and best practices from the industry and other jurisdictions. In keeping with the OCC‚Äôs risk-based approach to supervision, the OCC intends to appropriately tailor any resulting supervisory expectations to reflect differences in banks‚Äô circumstances such as complexity of operations and business models. General Principles Governance. An effective risk governance framework is essential to a bank‚Äôs safe and sound operation. A bank‚Äôs board and management should demonstrate an appropriate understanding of climate-related financial risk exposures and their impact on risk appetite to facilitate oversight. Sound governance includes reviewing information necessary to oversee the bank, allocating appropriate resources, assigning climate-related financial risk responsibilities throughout the organization (i.e., committees, reporting lines, and roles), and clearly communicating to staff regarding climate-related impacts to the bank‚Äôs risk profile. Responsibility and accountability may be integrated within existing organizational structures or by establishing new structures for climate-related financial risks. Where dedicated units are established, the board and management should clearly define these units‚Äô responsibilities and interaction with existing governance structures. The board should have adequate understanding and knowledge to assess the potential impact of climate-related risks on the bank and to address and oversee these risks within the bank‚Äôs strategy and risk appetite, including an understanding of the potential ways in which these risks could evolve over various time horizons and scenarios. Relevant time horizons may include those that extend beyond the bank‚Äôs typical strategic planning horizon. The board should actively oversee the bank‚Äôs risk-taking activities and hold management accountable for adhering to the risk governance framework. Management is responsible for executing the bank‚Äôs overall strategic plan. This responsibility includes effectively managing all risks, including climate- related financial risks, and their effects on the bank‚Äôs financial condition. Management should also hold staff accountable for controlling risks within established lines of authority and responsibility. Additionally, management is responsible for regularly reporting to the board on the level and nature of risks to the bank, including climate-related financial risks. Policies, Procedures, and Limits. Management should incorporate climate-related risks into policies, procedures, and limits to provide detailed guidance on the bank‚Äôs approach to these risks in line with the strategy and risk appetite set by the board. Policies, procedures, and limits should be modified when necessary to reflect the distinctive characteristics of climate-related risks and changes to the bank‚Äôs activities. Strategic Planning. The board and management should consider material climate-related financial risk exposures when setting the bank‚Äôs overall business strategy, risk appetite, and financial, capital, and operational plans. As part of forward-looking strategic planning, the board and management should address the potential impact of climate-related financial risk exposures on the bank‚Äôs financial condition, operations (including geographic locations), and business 2
objectives over various time horizons. The board and management should also consider climate- related financial risk impacts on stakeholders‚Äô expectations, the bank‚Äôs reputation, and LMI and other disadvantaged households and communities, including physical harm or access to bank products and services. The OCC recognizes that the incorporation of material climate-related financial risks into various planning processes is iterative as measurement methodologies, models, and data for analyzing these risks continue to evolve and mature over time. Any climate-related strategies, including any relevant corporate social responsibility objectives, should align with and support the bank‚Äôs broader strategy, risk appetite, and risk management framework. In addition, where banks engage in public communication of their climate-related strategies, boards and management should ensure that any public statements about their banks‚Äô climate-related strategies and commitments are consistent with their internal strategies and risk appetite statements. Risk Management. Climate-related financial risks typically impact banks through a range of traditional risk types. Management should oversee the development and implementation of processes to identify, measure, monitor, and control climate-related financial risk exposures within the bank‚Äôs existing risk management framework. A bank should employ a comprehensive process to identify emerging and material risks stemming from the bank‚Äôs business activities and associated exposures. The risk identification process should include input from stakeholders across the organization with relevant expertise (e.g., business units, independent risk management, and legal). Risk identification includes assessment of climate-related financial risks across a range of plausible scenarios and under various time horizons. As part of sound risk management, banks should develop processes to measure and monitor material climate-related financial risks and to inform management about the materiality of those risks. Material climate-related financial risk exposures should be clearly defined, aligned with the bank‚Äôs risk appetite, and supported by appropriate metrics (e.g., risk limits and key risk indicators) and escalation processes. Boards and management should also incorporate climate- related risks into their internal control frameworks, including internal audit. Tools and approaches for measuring and monitoring exposure to climate-related risks include, among others, exposure analysis, heat maps, climate risk dashboards, and scenario analysis. These tools can be leveraged to assess a bank‚Äôs exposure to both physical and transition risks in both the shorter and longer term. Outputs should inform the risk identification process and the short- and long-term financial risks to a bank‚Äôs business model from climate change. Data, Risk Measurement, and Reporting. Sound climate risk management depends on the availability of relevant, accurate, and timely data. Management should incorporate climate- related financial risk information into the bank‚Äôs internal reporting, monitoring, and escalation processes to facilitate timely and sound decision-making across the bank. Effective risk data aggregation and reporting capabilities allow management to capture and report material and emerging climate-related financial risk exposures, segmented or stratified by physical and transition risks, based upon the complexity and types of exposures. Data, risk measurement, modeling methodologies, and reporting continue to evolve at a rapid pace; management should monitor these developments and incorporate them into their climate risk management as warranted. 3
Scenario Analysis. Climate-related scenario analysis is emerging as an important approach for identifying, measuring, and managing climate-related risks. For the purposes of this guidance, climate-related scenario analysis refers to exercises used to conduct a forward-looking assessment of the potential impact on a bank of changes in the economy, financial system, or the distribution of physical hazards resulting from climate-related risks. These exercises differ from traditional stress testing exercises that typically assess the potential impacts of transitory shocks to near-term economic and financial conditions. An effective climate-related scenario analysis framework provides a comprehensive and forward-looking perspective that banks can apply alongside existing risk management practices to evaluate the resiliency of a bank‚Äôs strategy and risk management to the structural changes arising from climate-related risks. Management should develop and implement climate-related scenario analysis frameworks in a manner commensurate to the bank‚Äôs size, complexity, business activity, and risk profile. These frameworks should include clearly defined objectives that reflect the bank‚Äôs overall climate risk management strategies. These objectives could include, for example, exploring the impacts of climate-related risks on the bank‚Äôs strategy and business model, identifying and measuring vulnerability to relevant climate-related risk factors including physical and transition risks, and estimating climate-related exposures and potential losses across a range of plausible scenarios. In the near term, a climate-related scenario analysis framework can also assist the bank in identifying data and methodological limitations and uncertainty in climate risk management and informing the adequacy of its climate risk management framework. Climate-related scenario analyses should be subject to oversight, validation, and quality control standards that would be commensurate to their risk. Climate-related scenario analysis results should be clearly and regularly communicated to all relevant individuals within the bank, including an appropriate level of information necessary to effectively convey the assumptions, limitations, and uncertainty of results. Management of Risk Areas A risk assessment process is part of a sound risk governance framework, and it allows boards and management to identify emerging risks and to develop and implement appropriate strategies to mitigate those risks. Boards and management should consider and incorporate climate-related financial risks when identifying and mitigating all types of risk. These risk assessment principles describe how climate-related financial risks can be addressed in various risk categories. The OCC will elaborate on these risk assessment principles in subsequent guidance. Credit Risk. The board and management should consider climate-related financial risks as part of the underwriting and ongoing monitoring of portfolios. Effective credit risk management practices could include monitoring climate-related credit risks through sectoral, geographic, and single-name concentration analyses, including credit risk concentrations stemming from physical and transition risks. As part of concentration risk analysis, management should assess potential changes in correlations across exposures or asset classes. The board and management should determine credit risk appetite and lending limits related to these risks. 4
Liquidity Risk. Consistent with sound oversight and liquidity risk management, the board and management should assess whether climate-related financial risks could affect liquidity buffers and, if so, incorporate those risks into their liquidity risk management and liquidity buffers. Other Financial Risk. Management should monitor interest rate risk and other model inputs for greater volatility or less predictability due to climate-related financial risks. Where appropriate, management should include corresponding measures of conservatism in their risk measurements and controls. The board and management should monitor how climate-related financial risks affect the bank‚Äôs exposure to risk related to changing prices. While market participants are still researching how to measure climate price risk, the board and management should use the best measurement methodologies reasonably available to them and refine them over time. Operational Risk. The board and management should consider how climate-related financial risk exposures may adversely impact a bank‚Äôs operations, control environment, and operational resilience. Sound operational risk management includes incorporating an assessment across all business lines and operations, including third-party operations, and considering climate-related impacts on business continuity and the evolving legal and regulatory landscape. Legal/Compliance Risk. The board and management should consider how climate-related financial risks and risk mitigation measures affect the legal and regulatory landscape in which the bank operates. This consideration includes possible changes to legal requirements for, or underwriting considerations related to, flood or disaster-related insurance. It also includes possible fair lending concerns if the bank‚Äôs risk mitigation measures disproportionately affect communities or households on a prohibited basis such as race or ethnicity. Other Nonfinancial Risk. Consistent with sound oversight, the board and management should monitor how the execution of strategic decisions and the operating environment affect the bank‚Äôs financial condition and operational resilience as discussed in the strategic planning section. The board and management should also consider the extent to which the bank‚Äôs activities may increase the risk of negative financial impact from reputational damage, liability, or litigation, and implement adequate measures to account for these risks where material. Request for Feedback The OCC welcomes feedback on all aspects of these draft principles, including on the following questions. Among other uses, the OCC would consider responses in connection with developing any future guidance on climate-related financial risks. Refer to OCC Bulletin 2021-62 for instructions on submitting feedback. Applicability 1. Are there additional categories of banks (i.e., based on asset size, location, business model) to which these principles should apply? 5
Tailoring 2. How could future guidance assist a bank in developing its climate-related financial risk management practices commensurate to its size, complexity, risk profile, and scope of operations? General 3. What challenges do banks face in incorporating these principles into their risk management systems? How should the OCC further engage with banks to understand those challenges? Current Risk Management Practices 4. What specific tools or strategies have banks used to successfully incorporate climate-related financial risks into their risk management frameworks? 5. How do banks determine when climate-related financial risks are material and warrant greater than routine attention by the board and management? 6. What time horizon do banks consider relevant when identifying and assessing the materiality of climate-related financial risks? 7. What, if any, specific products, practices, and strategies‚Äìfor example, insurance or derivatives contracts or other capital market instruments‚Äìdo banks use to hedge, transfer, or mitigate climate-related financial risks? 8. What, if any, climate-related financial products or services‚Äìfor example, ‚Äúgreen bonds,‚Äù derivatives, dedicated investment funds, or other instruments that take climate-related considerations into account‚Äìdo banks offer to clients and customers?4 What risks, if any, do these products or services pose? 9. How do banks currently consider the impacts of climate-related financial risk mitigation strategies and financial products on households and communities, specifically LMI and other disadvantaged communities? Data, Disclosures, and Reporting 10. What, if any, specific climate-related data, metrics, tools, and models from borrowers and other counterparties do banks need to identify, measure, monitor, and control their own climate-related financial risks? How do banks currently obtain this information? What gaps and other concerns are there with respect to these data, metrics, tools, or models? 11. How could existing regulatory reporting requirements be augmented to better capture banks‚Äô exposure to climate-related financial risks? 4 ‚ÄúGreen bonds‚Äù refer to fixed-income securities, the proceeds of which are earmarked for environmentally beneficial investment. 6
Scenario Analysis 12. Scenario analysis is an important component of climate risk management that requires assumptions about plausible future states of the world. How do banks use climate scenario models, analysis, or tools and what challenges do they face? 13. What factors are most salient for the OCC to consider when designing and executing scenario analysis exercises? 7","The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) has proposed draft principles for managing climate-related financial risks in large banks, emphasizing the need for effective governance, strategic planning, and risk management. These principles address both physical risks (e.g., hurricanes, floods) and transition risks (e.g., policy shifts) associated with climate change. The OCC highlights the importance of integrating climate risks into banks' existing risk management frameworks, including governance, policies, strategic planning, and scenario analysis. The draft principles are targeted at banks with over $100 billion in assets, aiming to support their efforts in managing climate risks. The OCC seeks public feedback on these principles to refine future guidance, considering banks' size, complexity, and risk profiles. The proposal also addresses the potential disproportionate impact on financially vulnerable communities and emphasizes the need for banks to consider climate risks in credit, liquidity, operational, and legal risk management. The OCC invites feedback on various aspects, including applicability, challenges, tools, and data needs, to enhance banks' climate risk management practices."
kzh-m249-9za5,"Comptroller Hsu, We cannot continue to act as if the planet is not under existential threat by our continued and growing reliance on fossil fuels for building and transportation uses and generation of electricity.  I am very concerned about climate change and the lack of effort by our financial institutions to face this threat honestly and responsibly, and I thank you for this draft guidance. It outlines a framework for robust assessment, disclosure, and risk management that will force banks to reckon with climate change risk. I urge you to resist all efforts to dilute this guidance and to follow up with scope and details as broad as OCC‚Äôs authority allows. 
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change‚Äìa crisis that puts people of color and low-income communities, our financial system, and our planet at risk. 
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance recommendations to banks that they incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business, plan for climate change over a long time horizon and update models as additional data becomes available, develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures and metrics for setting limits, and make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. The OCC should also acknowledge that community banks are particularly vulnerable to climate risk and that the best way to reduce this risk is through reduced emissions.
It is in the best interests of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The comment addresses Comptroller Hsu, expressing concern over climate change and the reliance on fossil fuels. It supports the draft guidance for banks to assess, disclose, and manage climate risks, urging resistance to any dilution of this guidance. The commenter criticizes banks for investing in fossil fuels while claiming to address climate change, highlighting the risk to marginalized communities and the financial system. They advocate for banks to integrate climate risk management into all business levels, plan long-term, and align internal strategies with public commitments. The comment emphasizes the need for the OCC to ensure banks' actions match their zero carbon emission commitments and to consider climate risk in supervisory ratings. It calls for strong final guidance from the OCC to minimize climate risk and protect against unsafe banking practices."
kzh-m1er-l9tv,"I closely follow news associated with climate change and write a regular feature for the website Yale Climate Connections. One of the topics I follow is the financing of fossil fuel projects. It has become very, very clear that lending money to these projects is both a danger to the planet and its people and also financially risky. Therefore, I support the proposed guidance recommendations to banks that they incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business, plan for climate change over a long time horizon and update models as additional data becomes available, develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures and metrics for setting limits, and make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.","The commenter, who writes for Yale Climate Connections, emphasizes the risks associated with financing fossil fuel projects, highlighting both environmental and financial dangers. They express support for proposed guidance that urges banks to integrate climate-related risk management into all business levels. The recommendations include planning for long-term climate change, updating models with new data, defining climate-related risk exposures, setting metrics for limits, and ensuring internal strategies align with public climate commitments. The comment underscores the importance of these measures in mitigating risks and aligning financial practices with climate goals."
kzh-mjwf-nerc,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks.
I‚Äôm a grandmother, seriously concerned about the future of my grandchildren.
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk.
The claim of reducing ""climate intensity"" as a measure of compliance must be rejected. It is far too late for that to be a useful measure of financial climate benefit. Divestment from and minimizing of climate risk must be real, measurable outcomes of this policy.
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they:
Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business;
Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available;
Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits;
And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too.
It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The commenter, a concerned grandmother, thanks Comptroller Hsu for addressing climate change in banking. She criticizes banks for claiming to phase out financing for greenhouse gas emissions while still investing heavily in fossil fuels, which exacerbates climate change and endangers financial systems, marginalized communities, and the planet. She argues that the measure of reducing ""climate intensity"" is inadequate and calls for real, measurable outcomes in divestment and climate risk minimization. The commenter urges regulators to prevent banks from making short-term decisions that threaten the economy and communities. She supports the proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate change, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public commitments. She emphasizes that banks' climate risk management should influence their supervisory ratings and calls for the OCC to enforce strong guidance and remedies to ensure banks' actions align with their zero carbon emission commitments."
kzh-oxj0-paup,"Remember apartheid?  Noting would have changed in South Africa had it not been for divesting.  If we're to survive as a species we have to stop the generation of greenhouse gases, they trap heat and cause our planet to exhibit catastrophic events that are already devastating our lives and livelihoods.  You have the power to stop banks from funding the fossil fuels that are the recipe for our destruction.  Now is not soon enough","The comment draws a parallel between the historical divestment movement against apartheid in South Africa and the current need to divest from fossil fuels to combat climate change. The commenter argues that to ensure the survival of humanity, it is crucial to halt the generation of greenhouse gases, which are responsible for trapping heat and causing catastrophic environmental events. These events are already having devastating impacts on lives and livelihoods. The commenter urges action, emphasizing that financial institutions have the power to stop funding fossil fuels, which are seen as a major contributor to environmental destruction. The urgency of taking action is highlighted with the statement ""Now is not soon enough."""
kzh-noc8-3noe,"I am a grandmother deeply concerned about the future for my grandchildren and all children. Comptroller Hsu, I am very concerned about climate change and the lack of effort by our financial institutions to face this threat honestly and responsibly, and I thank you for this draft guidance. It outlines a framework for robust assessment, disclosure, and risk management that will force banks to reckon with climate change risk. I urge you to resist all efforts to dilute this guidance and to follow up with scope and details as broad as OCC‚Äôs authority allows. 
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change‚Äìa crisis that puts people of color and low-income communities, our financial system, and our planet at risk. 
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance recommendations to banks that they incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business, plan for climate change over a long time horizon and update models as additional data becomes available, develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures and metrics for setting limits, and make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. The OCC should also acknowledge that community banks are particularly vulnerable to climate risk and that the best way to reduce this risk is through reduced emissions.","The commenter, a concerned grandmother, expresses deep worry about climate change and the insufficient response from financial institutions. She appreciates Comptroller Hsu's draft guidance, which proposes a framework for banks to assess, disclose, and manage climate risks. The commenter urges the Comptroller to resist any dilution of this guidance and to expand its scope as much as possible. She criticizes banks for claiming to address climate change while still investing heavily in fossil fuels, which exacerbates the crisis, particularly affecting marginalized communities. The commenter supports the guidance's recommendations for banks to integrate climate risk management into all business levels, plan long-term, update models with new data, and ensure internal strategies align with public climate commitments. She emphasizes that banks' climate risk management should influence their supervisory ratings and highlights the vulnerability of community banks to climate risks, advocating for reduced emissions as a solution."
kzh-os1v-qa8w,"Climate Change is a huge topic.  Banking Regulations to manage proper risk management during a world-wide crisis is a task beyond me, and most of us.  Therefore, my comments are  at a high level.  If regulators implement strategies consistent with high-level reality, some good should result.       Since biblical times and before, humans were astute observers of their world.  They saw a ""limited goods"" paradigm where stability was a goal.  Their goal was usually ""honor,""  not wealth.  A saying: ""A rich man is either a thief, or the son of a thief.""  Castes were true in many societies, like India's.  Society cruised from generation with little change.  Change began about 1450 with the invention of movable type and the mass production of information. (Ts'ai Lun, inventer of paper, and Johann Gutenberg are rated #6 and #7 as the most infulential people in history--Michael H. Hart: THE 100.)  Isaac Newton triggered another change in 1687 describing physics and the calculus (he is #2 on Hart's THE 100).  Move forward to 1776: A group (#26 & 64) invented democracy, James Watt (#22) installed his first rotary steam engine, starting the Industrial revolution, and Adam Smith (#30) defined capitalism.  Each of these contributed to climate change, starting so slowly that the cumulative impact was not recognized until THE LIMITS TO GROWTH (1972) was published about two centuries later.  The triple momentum increase of self-government, stored energy capture, and fake but self-serving economics has put us on a new path to self-destruction.        Religion has been part of cultural development for at least 1000 generations.  ""Territoriality"" has also molded human behavior for much longer.  Human behavior today is a combination of what we have learned through our cultures (which can be unlearned and relearned) and behavior embedded in our genes through natural selection.  Economist Jeffrey D. Sachs describes territoriality in just two sentences:   ‚ÄúSince the great dispersal from Africa [about 70,000 years ago], and surely before that within Africa, human groups have battled each other for territory and to secure their basic survival needs (including water, food supplies, shelter and minerals).  Indeed, human nature was forged in the cauldron of territorial competition, which instilled in our genes and our cultures a remarkable ability to cooperate within a group, combined with a deeply rooted tendency toward conflict and distrust between groups (according to race, religion, language, national origin, and other markers of identity).‚Äù          Territories are dominated by the alpha males who stake them out.  He permits cooperating males to remain; competitive males are ejected from the group, and their survivability without group protection declines drastically.  Therefore loyalty to the alpha male leader is paramount.  A modern example of territorial behavior is Donald Trump, who cowed his entire group, Republicans, into mindless support.  Note also that the captains of industry are typically alpha males as CEOs of corporations, the foundation of capitalism. Capitalism is a deeply flawed economic system based of flawed assumptions, and seeking inequality between its alpha male owners and their workers, who, in most cases, are the major capital.  It assumes natural capital has no value, and pollution has no cost.  The stock market is fake, and will crash as soon as people realize most stock represents expectations, not value.  Banks are at the top of the vulnerability list.  Capitalism will also crash because its basic assumption, that growth has no limit, violates the laws of physics, and in particular the laws of conservation of mass, energy and momentum.  The momentum (mass times velocity) of the economy is limited when the mass of humanity stops growing.  The population has already overshot its sustainable limits, and collapse will come shortly.  From a physics point of view, Covid-19 helped.  From a social point of view, Covid is a nightmare.         Bottom line: you have your work cut out.  My advice: Hire Jeffrey D. Sachs.  He understand the world very well.  Do not trust energy or capital (bank) capitalists.  Alpha males typically look out for themselves first. John W (Elders Climate Action-Oregon)","The comment discusses the historical and cultural evolution of human society and its impact on climate change and economic systems. It highlights the shift from stability-focused societies to those driven by capitalism and industrialization, which have contributed to climate change. The author critiques capitalism as a flawed system that values inequality and disregards natural resources and pollution costs. The comment also touches on human territorial behavior, likening it to modern political and corporate leadership, particularly criticizing figures like Donald Trump and corporate CEOs as ""alpha males."" The author suggests that the current economic model is unsustainable and predicts a collapse due to overpopulation and resource limits. The comment concludes by advising regulators to hire economist Jeffrey D. Sachs for his understanding of global issues and warns against trusting capitalists focused on energy and banking."
kzh-t0ll-3ijb,"Given the acceleration of global warming impact on disastrous weather events worldwide, it is imperative that lending institutions be aware that lending and investing in the fossil fuel industry is becoming more of a risk each year.  This risk could put our economy in jeopardy.","The comment emphasizes the increasing risks associated with lending and investing in the fossil fuel industry due to the acceleration of global warming and its impact on disastrous weather events worldwide. It argues that these risks could jeopardize the economy, suggesting that lending institutions should be aware of the growing financial dangers linked to fossil fuel investments."
kzh-qnir-2nfz,"Comptroller Hsu, I am very concerned about climate change and the lack of effort by our financial institutions to face this threat honestly and responsibly, and I thank you for this draft guidance. It outlines a framework for robust assessment, disclosure, and risk management that will force banks to reckon with climate change risk. I urge you to resist all efforts to dilute this guidance and to follow up with scope and details as broad as OCC‚Äôs authority allows.","The commenter expresses concern about climate change and criticizes financial institutions for not addressing the threat adequately. They appreciate Comptroller Hsu's draft guidance, which proposes a framework for assessment, disclosure, and risk management related to climate change risks. The commenter urges Comptroller Hsu to resist any attempts to weaken this guidance and to ensure that the scope and details are as comprehensive as the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency's (OCC) authority permits."
kzh-rx4t-ip4e,"Investing in the fossil fuel industry is increasingly high risk with dwindling reserves (ExxonMobil's recent writing down 39% of their proven reserves) and the mounting legal, regulatory, and health related consequences of fossil fuel extraction. Clean up of the pollution caused by mountain top removal in Appalachia is costing the coal company Patriot $400 million dollars and that's just clean up. Research on the impact on public health is closing in on proving links to cancer and progressive respiratory diseases from pollutants released in the air and affecting ground water in population far downstream from the destruction. It's time for banks to stop lending money to energy industries which are destroying the environment, causing near populations to fall terminally ill, all for an extractive industry whose reserves are depleting. Calculating the risks, it seems prudent to invest in solar and wind generated energy which is clean and renewable, creating good, safe and clean jobs for Americans.","The comment argues against investing in the fossil fuel industry due to its high risks and negative impacts. It highlights the dwindling reserves, citing ExxonMobil's reduction of proven reserves by 39%, and the significant costs associated with environmental cleanup, such as Patriot Coal's $400 million expense for pollution caused by mountain top removal. The comment also points to emerging research linking fossil fuel pollutants to cancer and respiratory diseases, affecting populations far from extraction sites. It urges banks to cease funding these environmentally damaging industries, which contribute to severe health issues and are based on depleting resources. Instead, the comment advocates for investment in solar and wind energy, emphasizing their clean, renewable nature and potential to create safe, sustainable jobs in the U.S."
kzh-s9l0-caut,"Comptroller Hsu, 
Thank you for this draft guidance for banks to responsibly address the risks of the climate crisis in carrying out their business. This measure is a good first step to force banks to reckon with the climate change risks and be transparent about what they are really doing in this area.  Please stand firm and resist efforts by the banks and fossil fuels lobbyists to dilute this guidance.  As a citizen very worried about the climate crisis and its present and future impacts on our children, communities and planet, I urge you to take  notice that banks continue to invest billions into companies that produce fossil fuels despite their public statements of taking the climate crisis seriously.  Their deeds need to match their words!
I support the proposed guidance recommendations to banks that they incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business and make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate statements.  Recently, I reviewed my retirement accounts with a large financial institution to make sure that my portfolio was sound, well balanced and free of fossil fuels companies - as I am about to retire.  I had to dig to get the information on fossil fuels investments in the fund and was aghast to find out there was a sizable amount invested in fossil fuels companies.  Putting aside the morality of continuing to invest in an industry that is destroying our communities and planet, how could this be prudent investing from a financial perspective?  At a minimum, banks must be forced to clearly disclose to their customers the fossil fuels involvement in the products they are offering.  I certainly don't want to have my life's savings be used by banks to continue enabling the fossil fuels industry.  I should not have to spend hours trying to figure this out.
In closing, I ask you to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk and unsound bank practices in this area.  The climate situation is urgent and the OCC needs to issue guidance with teeth in this area now.","The commenter expresses gratitude for the draft guidance aimed at banks to address climate crisis risks, viewing it as a positive initial step. They urge Comptroller Hsu to resist pressure from banks and fossil fuel lobbyists to weaken the guidance. The commenter highlights the discrepancy between banks' public statements on climate change and their continued investments in fossil fuels, urging alignment between their actions and words. They support the guidance's recommendation for banks to integrate climate risk management into all business levels and ensure internal strategies match public climate commitments. The commenter shares a personal experience of discovering fossil fuel investments in their retirement portfolio, emphasizing the need for banks to transparently disclose such investments. They argue that investing in fossil fuels is not only morally questionable but also financially imprudent. The commenter calls for strong, enforceable guidance from the OCC to address climate risks and unsound banking practices, stressing the urgency of the climate crisis."
kzi-bqmu-pp5x,"Dear Commissioner Hsu, I applaud and support the OCC's detailed and critically needed plan. It is needed to restrict the billions of dollars that banks are investing in companies producing fossil fuels. The public and banks must act NOW to minimize climate risk. Your plan will stop the unsafe risk-taking, unsound practices by large banks and require remedies. I am a 76-year-old grandmother living in Gainesville, Florida. I work with Elder Climate Action and the Alachua County League of Women Voters. In 2014, I began investing in Fossil fuel-free funds for my 5 grandchildren. I avoid banks and use my local credit union. Thank you for acting on behalf of America's children and the planet.","The commenter expresses strong support for the OCC's plan to restrict bank investments in fossil fuel companies, emphasizing the urgency of minimizing climate risk. They commend the plan for addressing unsafe risk-taking and unsound practices by large banks. The commenter, a 76-year-old grandmother from Gainesville, Florida, is actively involved in climate action groups and has personally invested in fossil fuel-free funds for her grandchildren. She advocates for using local credit unions over banks and thanks the OCC for taking action to protect future generations and the planet."
kzh-tp12-jo8r,"Comptroller Hsu, I am very concerned about climate change and the lack of effort by our financial institutions to face this threat honestly and responsibly, and I thank you for this draft guidance. I know that some banks may be taking some steps already, but as a bank customer it's almost impossible to know and trust what is being done. I think it would be very valuable for your office to set some strict parameters for what banks must do. Therefore, I support the proposed guidance recommendations to banks that they incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business, plan for climate change over a long time horizon and update models as additional data becomes available. It is in the best interests of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.
Thank you.","The commenter expresses concern about climate change and the insufficient efforts by financial institutions to address this issue. They appreciate the draft guidance proposed by Comptroller Hsu and emphasize the need for strict parameters for banks to follow. The commenter supports the guidance recommendations for banks to integrate climate-related risk management into all business levels, plan for long-term climate change, and update models with new data. They argue that it is in the public's and banks' best interests to act now to minimize climate risk. The commenter urges the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) to use its authority to issue strong final guidance on climate risk, protect against unsafe banking practices, and require banks to implement necessary remedies."
kzh-v021-vw0y,"Comptroller Hsu, I am a mother very concerned about the effect of climate change on young people and future generations.  I don't believe our financial institutions have faced this threat honestly and responsibly, and I thank you for this draft guidance. I am pleased it outlines a framework for robust assessment, disclosure, and risk management that will force banks to reckon with climate change risk. I urge you to resist all efforts to dilute this guidance and to follow up with scope and details as broad as OCC‚Äôs authority allows. 
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change‚Äìa crisis that puts people of color and low-income communities here in Northern California and elsewhere, our financial system, and our planet at risk. 
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance recommendations to banks that they incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business, plan for climate change over a long time horizon and update models as additional data becomes available, develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures and metrics for setting limits, and make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. The OCC should also acknowledge that community banks are particularly vulnerable to climate risk and that the best way to reduce this risk is through reduced emissions.
It is in the best interests of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The commenter, a concerned mother, supports Comptroller Hsu's draft guidance on climate change risk management for financial institutions. She appreciates the framework for assessment, disclosure, and risk management, urging resistance to any dilution of the guidance. The commenter criticizes banks for investing in fossil fuels despite public claims of addressing climate change, highlighting the risk to marginalized communities and the financial system. She advocates for banks to incorporate climate risk management at all business levels, plan long-term, update models with new data, and align internal strategies with public commitments. The commenter emphasizes the need for the OCC to ensure banks' actions match their net-zero carbon commitments and to factor climate risk management into supervisory ratings. She also notes community banks' vulnerability to climate risk and the importance of reducing emissions. The commenter calls for the OCC to issue strong final guidance, protect against unsafe practices, and require banks to take necessary actions to minimize climate risk."
kzi-kg0l-hsjv,"February 11, 2022 Chief Counsel‚Äôs Office Office of the Comptroller of the Currency 400 7th St. SW, Suite 3E-218 Washington, DC 20219 Re: Docket ID OCC-2021-0023, Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks To Whom It May Concern: On behalf of the Center for American Progress, I write to comment on the Comptroller of the Currency‚Äôs (OCC) request for information titled Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks (RFI).1 We greatly appreciate the OCC‚Äôs leadership in developing this document and for providing the opportunity to comment. The OCC has rightly recognized the ‚Äúeffects of climate change and the transition to a low carbon economy as presenting emerging risks to banks and the financial system,‚Äù and that ‚Äú[w]eaknesses in how banks identify, measure, monitor, and control the potential physical and transition risks associated with a changing climate could adversely affect a bank‚Äôs safety and soundness.‚Äù When building on the principles articulated in the RFI in subsequent guidance in the future, the OCC should: ‚Ä¢ apply its principles to all banks; ‚Ä¢ issue tailored guidance when appropriate; ‚Ä¢ ensure examiners‚Äô interactions with banks on climate risks is tailored; ‚Ä¢ confirm banks adhere to their public climate commitments; ‚Ä¢ allow banks to only use carbon offsets that are substantiated to meet environmental commitments; ‚Ä¢ ensure banks provide fair and equitable access to financial services; ‚Ä¢ require large- and mid-size regional banks to engage in scenario analyses; and ‚Ä¢ help banks collect adequate data to analyze their climate risks. Scope of the principles Although the OCC limits its principles for climate-related financial risk management to institutions ‚Äúwith over $100 billion in total consolidated assets,‚Äù the principles themselves are sufficiently high-level to apply to all banks, regardless of size, location, and business model. For example, the OCC explains that ‚Äúa bank‚Äôs board and management should demonstrate an appropriate understanding of climate-related financial risk exposures and 1 Comptroller of the Currency, ‚ÄúPrinciples for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks,‚Äù December 16, 2021, available at https://www.occ.treas.gov/news-issuances/bulletins/2021/bulletin-2021- 62a.pdf.
their impact on risk appetite to facilitate oversight,‚Äù as well as that ‚Äúa bank should employ a comprehensive process to identify emerging and material risks stemming from the bank‚Äôs business activities and associated exposures.‚Äù The OCC notes that ‚Äúall banks, regardless of size, may have material exposures to climate-related financial risks,‚Äù and the principles articulated apply just as much to a bank with $500 billion in assets as a bank with $50 billion or $5 billion. While the OCC should apply the principles to all banks, it should differentiate in the implementation of these principles. Implementation will clearly differ based on factors the OCC listed (i.e., asset size, location, business model) and others. Tailored guidance As the OCC articulates new climate related principles and expectations for how banks will implement those principles, it should consider (on a document-by-document basis) whether or how those principles or expectations may be tailored to banks‚Äô business lines or sizes. The OCC should also consider whether banks with particular business lines or banks that operate in particular locations require tailored guidance. For example, banks with high concentrations of mortgage loans will have different risk profiles from banks with high concentrations of agricultural loans, and banks with high concentrations of mortgage loans in one area of the country will have different risk profiles from banks in others. The OCC should tailor its expectations for how banks will mitigate their risks faced, and it would be appropriate for the OCC to issue guidance specifying what those tailored expectations are. Examiners‚Äô interactions with banks Just as the OCC should tailor its written guidance, its examiners‚Äô interactions with banks should be similarly tailored. Some of the largest institutions are keenly aware of their climate risks and began taking steps to mitigate those risks even before the OCC issued its guidance.2 For these institutions, examiners‚Äô climate-related responsibilities should be focused on, for example, ensuring that banks‚Äô managements have put forth policies and procedures based on the most recent science, and that staff comply with those policies and procedures. However, for smaller institutions that may not have the resources to begin adapting to the realities of climate change, examiners should have conversations with banks‚Äô boards and management so that they understand their institutions face climate- related risks and have basic information as to the range of possible responses. Banks‚Äô public commitments We strongly support the OCC‚Äôs statement that, ‚Äúwhere banks engage in public communication of their climate-related strategies, boards and management should ensure that any public statements about their banks‚Äô climate-related strategies and commitments are consistent with their internal strategies and risk appetite statements.‚Äù Although the OCC cannot legally mandate that banks make specific public commitments regarding their loan portfolios, it should ensure that banks articulate measurable targets and take the steps necessary to adhere to those targets when commitments are made. 2 For example, six U.S. headquartered global systemically important banks have joined the Net-Zero Banking Alliance. See Net-Zero Banking Alliance, ‚ÄúMembers,‚Äù (last accessed February 7, 2022), available at https://www.unepfi.org/net-zero-banking/members/.
When a bank fails to adhere to its public commitments on climate change, it faces losses for both reputational and legal reasons. First, banks that make extensive climate commitments, such as commitments to be net zero by 2050, may lose customers if they fail to make significant progress on those commitments, as individuals who choose where to bank based on climate pledges may move their business away from institutions that fail to make progress on their commitments. Second, publicly traded banks that make climate commitments may face litigation under the securities laws for making materially false statements if they similarly fail to make significant progress on those commitments. To help banks avoid losses from these risks, the OCC should make clear that banks that make public climate commitments must develop and implement credible strategies for fulfilling those commitments. Importantly, those strategies should not rely on carbon offsets, which are ‚Äútradable ‚Äòrights‚Äô or certificates linked to activities that lower the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.‚Äù3 Not only is there deep concern that many carbon offsets, as currently designed, do not work,4 but regulators with jurisdiction over carbon markets may bring enforcement actions against sellers of offsets for fraud, severely limiting the supply and increasing the price of legitimate offsets.5 To the extent banks wish to rely on carbon offsets to meet their commitments, the OCC should ensure that efforts are in place to substantiate that those offsets result in the removal of carbon from the atmosphere. Fair and equitable access to financial services The OCC‚Äôs principles note that climate change ‚Äúcould include potentially disproportionate impact on the financially vulnerable, including low- to moderate-income (LMI) and other disadvantaged households and communities,‚Äù and, accordingly, it is especially important that the OCC help ensure banks continue to provide services to these households and communities. Although there may be additional means of tackling this, the OCC should take two specific actions. First, it should issue guidance detailing how banks may continue extending credit to vulnerable communities in a safe and sound manner. The OCC should particularly focus on how banks may lend for the purchase and installation of residential solar panels, which are the types of high-dollar, long-term loans that bank examiners are traditionally reticent for banks to make. Second, the OCC should work with the other federal banking agencies to update their Community Reinvestment Act (CRA) rules to ensure that credit flows to LMI and other disadvantaged communities to help reduce their fossil fuel emissions and to protect themselves from climate impacts. Currently, banking deserts‚Äìoften in central cities and rural areas‚Äìare excluded from the benefits promised by the CRA because they are not in any institution‚Äôs assessment area. The OCC should update its CRA regulations to ensure that banks with a nationwide presence direct investment into all underserved 3 See e.g., Angelo Gurgel, ‚ÄúCarbon Offsets,‚Äù MIT Climate Portal, September 11, 2020, available at https://climate.mit.edu/explainers/carbon-offsets. 4 See e.g., Lisa Song and Paula Moura, ‚ÄúAn Even More Inconvenient Truth: Why Carbon Credits for Forest Preservation May Be Worse Than Nothing,‚Äù ProPublica, May 22, 2019, available at https://features.propublica.org/brazil-carbon-offsets/inconvenient-truth-carbon-credits-dont-work- deforestation-redd-acre-cambodia/. 5 Todd Phillips, ‚ÄúA Climate and Competition Agenda for the Commodity Futures Trading Commission,‚Äù American Progress, February 1, 2022, available at https://www.americanprogress.org/article/a-climate-and- competition-agenda-for-the-commodity-futures-trading-commission/ (‚ÄúThe CFTC has jurisdiction over carbon offsets through its authority to address fraud and market manipulation in spot commodity markets‚Ä¶and it can hold offset issuers accountable if they promise carbon reductions that do not, or simply cannot, occur.‚Äù).
communities, not only those surrounding physical branches. Further, the OCC should explore a climate resilience and environmental justice finance mandate for the CRA, which would give banks credit for providing loans for projects such as energy efficient and climate resilient affordable housing, installation of community solar energy projects, and others.6 Scenario analyses and data collection When developing climate scenario analysis guidance, we encourage the OCC to keep in mind several key points.7 First, we note that it is not necessary for the OCC‚Äôs initial guidance or scenarios to be perfect. Scenario analysis is an evolving effort that will improve after each iteration. Rather, it is important for banks to begin conducting their analyses quickly in order to learn from them. We recommend the OCC utilize the scenarios for the National Climate Assessment as a basis for its initial scenarios,8 as well as resources developed by other federal agencies, such as the Environmental Protection Agency‚Äôs summaries of research investigating the sectoral impacts of climate change.9 Second, in addition to banks with assets above $100 billion, mid-size, regional banks should be required to undertake climate-related scenario analyses as well. Regional bank, with portfolios that may not be as diversified as those of larger banks, may experience higher rates of failure and branch closures as a consequence of natural disasters that affect only one part of the nation. Accordingly, safety and soundness concerns necessitate climate scenario analyses for mid-size institutions, though those analyses may not need to be as rigorous as the ones for larger banks so long as they help banks gain a better understanding of the climate risks they face. Third, the OCC should ensure that banks collect or otherwise have access to the data necessary to understand their portfolios‚Äô and operations‚Äô climate risks and adapt accordingly. The OCC should provide guidance detailing best practices for collecting or otherwise obtaining climate-related data. The OCC should also engage with the Securities and Exchange Commission in its forthcoming climate change disclosure rule to help ensure that banks which hold debt or equity of public companies can use that information to understand their portfolio risks.10 *** 6 See generally Michela Zonta and Caius Willingham, ‚ÄúA CRA To Meet the Challenge of Climate Change,‚Äù American Progress, December 17, 2020, available at https://www.americanprogress.org/article/cra-meet- challenge-climate-change/. 7 The OCC‚Äôs principles describe ‚Äúclimate-related scenario analysis‚Äù as ‚Äúexercises used to conduct a forward- looking assessment of the potential impact on a bank of changes in the economy, financial system, or the distribution of physical hazards resulting from climate-related risks.‚Äù 8 U.S. Global Change Research Program, ‚ÄúScenarios for the National Climate Assessment,‚Äù (last accessed February 7, 2022), available at https://scenarios.globalchange.gov/. 9 U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, ‚ÄúTechnical Documentation on The Framework for Evaluating Damages and Impacts (FrEDI)‚Äù at 15‚Äì16, October 2021, available at https://www.epa.gov/system/files/documents/2021-10/technical-documentation-on-the-framework-for- evaluating-damages-and-impacts_maintext.pdf. 10 RIN: 3235-AM87, (last accessed February 7, 2022), available at https://www.reginfo.gov/public/do/eAgendaViewRule?pubId=202110&RIN=3235-AM87.
Thank you again for the opportunity to comment on the RFI. Sincerely, Mr. Todd Phillips Director, Financial Regulation and Corporate Governance 202.495.3699 [direct] tphillips@americanprogress.org","The Center for American Progress appreciates the OCC's initiative on climate-related financial risk management for large banks. They urge the OCC to apply these principles to all banks, regardless of size, and to issue tailored guidance based on banks' business lines and locations. The comment emphasizes the need for banks to adhere to public climate commitments and suggests that carbon offsets should be substantiated. It highlights the importance of fair access to financial services for vulnerable communities and recommends updating the Community Reinvestment Act to support climate resilience. The comment also advocates for scenario analyses for mid-size banks and stresses the need for adequate data collection to assess climate risks. Overall, the Center supports the OCC's efforts but calls for broader application and tailored implementation of the principles."
kzi-ktuc-vybx,"Comptroller Hsu,I have been alerted to your request for comments from the American public by an alliance of concerned citizens, or a citizens lobby, Elders for Climate Action.  Although my concerns and the details as they apply to your agency may be similar when others of us contact you, this does not mean that you can nor should you disregard our concerns.    I am a grandmother who has been working for the climate since the first Earth Day at my Aurora, Colorado high school in 1970.  Although there were so many times the USA could have begun to mitigate the damage caused by fossil fuel burning, we have only allowed things to get worse and worse until now we are running out of time.  Therefore, I urge you to consider the points in this comment even if others contact you with the same talking points.  I am very concerned about climate change and the lack of effort by our financial institutions to face this threat honestly and responsibly, and I thank you for this draft guidance. It outlines a framework for robust assessment, disclosure, and risk management that will force banks to reckon with climate change risk. I urge you to resist all efforts to dilute this guidance and to follow up with scope and details as broad as OCC‚Äôs authority allows. 
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change‚Äìa crisis that puts people of color and low-income communities, our financial system, and our planet at risk. 
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance recommendations to banks that they incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business, plan for climate change over a long time horizon and update models as additional data becomes available, develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures and metrics for setting limits, and make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. The OCC should also acknowledge that community banks are particularly vulnerable to climate risk and that the best way to reduce this risk is through reduced emissions.
It is in the best interests of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The commenter, a member of Elders for Climate Action, expresses deep concern about climate change and the role of financial institutions in exacerbating the crisis. They emphasize the need for the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) to enforce robust climate risk management guidelines for banks. The commenter highlights the discrepancy between banks' public commitments to reducing greenhouse gas emissions and their continued investments in fossil fuels, which disproportionately affect marginalized communities. They support the proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management into all business levels, plan for long-term climate impacts, and ensure internal strategies align with public climate commitments. The commenter urges the OCC to use its authority to issue strong guidance, protect against unsafe banking practices, and require banks to take necessary actions to minimize climate risk. They also note the vulnerability of community banks to climate risks and advocate for reduced emissions as a mitigation strategy."
kzi-so8q-9les,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks.
This comment is from the Chair of the Legislative Working Group of 1000 Grandmothers for Future Generations.  We want our grandchildren to have a viable future!
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk.
Divestment from and minimizing of climate risk must be real, measurable outcomes of this policy.  The claim of reducing ""climate intensity"" as a measure of compliance must be rejected.  
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need to stop having the banks' short-term business decisions endanger our economy, our communities, and the sustainability of our human habitat.
I support the following proposed recommendations to banks that they:
Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business;
Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available;
Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits;
And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too.
It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.
Thank you for your attention to these matters.
Barbara Rhine 1000 Grandmothers for Future Generations Chair, Legislative Working Group","The comment, from Barbara Rhine of 1000 Grandmothers for Future Generations, addresses Comptroller Hsu on the issue of climate change and banks. It criticizes banks for investing in fossil fuels despite claims of addressing climate change, highlighting the risk to the financial system, marginalized communities, and the planet. The comment calls for genuine, measurable divestment from fossil fuels and rejects ""climate intensity"" as a compliance measure. It urges regulators to prevent banks from making short-term decisions that threaten the economy and environment. Recommendations include integrating climate risk management at all business levels, planning for long-term climate change, defining risk exposures, and aligning internal strategies with public commitments. The comment stresses the importance of the OCC ensuring banks' actions align with their zero carbon emissions commitments and factoring climate risk management into supervisory ratings. It advocates for strong guidance from the OCC to minimize climate risk and protect against unsafe banking practices."
kzi-z1o1-zcvb,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Since the Paris Agreement was signed in 2015, the largest banks have invested more than $3.8 trillion in oil, gas, and coal production. JPMorgan Chase, Chase, Wells Fargo and Bank of America have loaned more money to the fossil fuel industry than any other banks in the world.  Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. We must hold banks accountable for their investments in fossil fuels.  Leading climate scientists released in their report described as ""code red for humanity,"" a warning that ""unless there are immediate, rapid and large-scale reductions in greenhouse gas emissions,"" the status quo will lead to 1.5 degrees Celsius by the early 2030s. 
If we collectively fail to curb greenhouse gas emissions in the 2020s rapidly, the consequences will be even more severe. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available;  3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments. The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The comment addresses the issue of climate change and banks' investments in fossil fuels. Despite public claims of addressing climate change, banks have invested over $3.8 trillion in fossil fuels since the Paris Agreement. Major banks like JPMorgan Chase, Wells Fargo, and Bank of America are highlighted for their significant contributions to fossil fuel financing. The comment argues that these investments exacerbate climate change, posing risks to the financial system, marginalized communities, and the planet. It urges regulators to hold banks accountable and push for urgent action to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. The commenter supports proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, and align internal strategies with public climate commitments. They emphasize the need for the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) to enforce strong guidance and ensure banks' actions align with their zero-carbon commitments, factoring climate risk management into supervisory ratings."
kzi-zdom-s124,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks.  As a Michigan Catholic, and director of a network of Catholics in Michigan who are supportive of immigrants -- we know many are coming here because of Climate Crisis. 
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The commenter, a Michigan Catholic and director of a network supporting immigrants, thanks Comptroller Hsu for addressing climate change in banking. They highlight the contradiction between banks' public commitments to climate action and their continued investments in fossil fuels, which exacerbate climate change and threaten financial systems, marginalized communities, and the planet. The commenter urges regulators to prevent banks from making short-term decisions that endanger the economy and communities. They support proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public commitments. The commenter emphasizes the importance of banks' climate risk management in supervisory ratings and calls for the OCC to enforce strong guidance to ensure banks' actions align with their zero carbon emission commitments, protecting against unsafe practices and requiring remedies where necessary."
kzj-igte-41ij,"I am a retired professor of education, and I've studied and taught about the nature of value and the value of diversity in economics, ethics, and education. I devote my time now to the money question, and I am striving, with others, to ""end banking,"" banking defined as McMillan (2014) does as ""the creation of money out of credit"" (pp. 3, 6, 179; see also pp. 21, 31, 37, 56, 58, 113, 115, 140, 159, & 179). 
That is, we need much more out of the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency than asking banks to track and account for the risks caused by climate change. We need to supersede what we currently use as money--which is private interest-bearing credit created by commercial banks via keystrokes when we agree to pay them that amount over time with interest--with a public asset created and spent, lent, given, or invested into circulation for the public good by the people through our democratically elected representatives. Doing so would eliminate the growth imperative that is leading to the climate change and environmental crises that your ""Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks"" are merely trying to account for. That is their shortcoming. It is too little too late. 
That said, these principles ARE needed and warranted today. They definitely need to be implemented not merely to secure the bottom line of the banks and of the people whose deposits reside under their auspices, but also to put attention on the detrimental consequences for all, including banks, of our blind and exploitive profit-driven practices that are polluting and destroying the natural environment and gift economy that, last I looked, you and I and all of us depend upon for our lives. 
But your new principles do not go far enough. Why are you only requiring banks to factor in the risks exacerbated by climate change rather than requiring them at least not to increase those risks by their investments and, preferably, to mitigate against them? It is not like the lives of your grandchildren and mine do not depend upon us stopping business as usual. They do. And the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency is a public agency that can and should lead the way, and if--or when--existing law under the Federal Reserve Act gets in your way from stopping banks from creating via interest-bearing loans what we use as legal tender, then you must work to get Congress to change that law. Only then will your ""principles for climate-related financial risk management"" hold water and credibility with the 99%, not just of the US but of the global monetary system that, after WWII, we've made subservient to our Federal Reserve Note. 
Thank you for requesting public comment and considering mine.","The commenter, a retired professor of education, argues for a fundamental change in the monetary system, criticizing the current practice of banks creating money through credit. They advocate for replacing this system with a public asset model managed by democratically elected representatives to address climate change and environmental crises. The commenter believes the current ""Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks"" are insufficient, as they only require banks to account for climate risks rather than actively mitigate them. They urge the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to lead in reforming the monetary system and to push for legislative changes if necessary, emphasizing the urgency of these actions for future generations and global stability."
