kzl-enzj-msra,"Sunday, February 13, 2022
OCC Headquarters 400 7th St. SW Washington, DC 20219
Subject: Use the full extent of your authority to curtail banks‚Äô investments in climate change -- Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks (Document ID: OCC-2021-0023-0001)
To Comptroller Hsu:
Thank you for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. The public supports the new guidance telling big banks to mitigate climate risks.
Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and announce new climate plans in which they will phase out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks' continued investments in fossil fuels are directly fueling the climate crisis‚Äîa crisis that puts people of color and low-income communities, our financial system, and our planet at risk. 
Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance's recommendations to banks that they:
1. incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business;
2. plan for climate change over a long-time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available;
3. develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; and
4. make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) must ensure that banks' actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks' management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. The OCC should also acknowledge that community banks are particularly vulnerable to climate risk, and that the best way to reduce this risk is through reduced emissions.
It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.
""The ultimate test of a moral society is the kind of world that it leaves to its children."" -- Dietrich Bonhoeffer
Thank you for your consideration of my comments. Please do NOT add my name to your mailing list. I will learn about future developments on this issue from other sources.
