William Michael Cunningham Economist and Impact Investing Researcher info@creativeinvest.com www.creativeinvest.com 13","William Michael Cunningham, an economist and impact investing researcher, submitted a public comment to the Acting Comptroller of the Currency, Michael J. Hsu, regarding the OCC's draft principles for managing climate-related financial risks. Cunningham criticizes the OCC and other regulatory bodies for incompetence and racial discrimination, stating that further input would be futile. He highlights his long-standing concerns about regulatory failures to protect the public interest, citing past instances where he warned about financial malfeasance and systemic risks. Cunningham emphasizes his extensive experience in financial innovation and ethics, noting his contributions to creating financial instruments for underserved communities. Despite his expertise, he claims his offers to consult with regulatory agencies have been rejected due to discrimination. Cunningham argues that current regulatory practices favor a small group of non-African American individuals, harming the public and the country's economic prospects. He predicts that if trends continue, the number of FDIC-insured institutions will drastically decrease, which would not benefit the public. Cunningham's comment underscores his commitment to protecting public interest and advocating for fair financial practices."
kzn-moj7-j8qm,"Docket ID OCC-2021-0023 Comments of Jupiter Intelligence on the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency‚Äôs Draft Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks February 14, 2022 Jupiter Intelligence (Jupiter) appreciates the opportunity to submit these comments in response to the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency‚Äôs (OCC) Request for Feedback on its draft ‚ÄúPrinciples for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks.‚Äù1 Jupiter is a company that predicts risks from weather and climate change. Jupiter‚Äôs data analytics and services help public and private sector entities assess and manage the physical risks of extreme weather events, often referred to as perils, including floods, wildfires, or hurricanes. Jupiter‚Äôs world-class ClimateScore‚Ñ¢ risk platform provides extremely accurate predictions ‚Äì at exceptionally high spatial resolutions ‚Äì of extreme weather events from the asset to the portfolio level, and in time horizons ranging from a few hours to several decades from now. Jupiter‚Äôs products combine weather prediction, climate and engineering models, and cutting-edge machine learning (ML), cloud computing, satellite data, and more. As of this submission, one-half of the U.S.‚Äôs largest banks and government sponsored enterprises subscribe to Jupiter‚Äôs climate analytics services, including what apparently is the most advanced and sophisticated bank implementation to date. Additionally, Jupiter‚Äôs tools are already used by several federal, state, and city agencies, as well as by a broad range of private sector entities across critical infrastructure sectors, including the financial, insurance, energy, and housing sectors.2 While Jupiter is not the only company or entity with this type of tool, the company is widely regarded as one of the leaders in market adoption, science, and technology. When decision makers have access to such weather and climate risk prediction capabilities, they are better able to make informed planning and operational decisions that drive superior risk management, risk disclosure, and investment in resilient infrastructure in both short- and long- term time horizons that will help improve the resilience of infrastructure assets. In fact, WIRED Magazine wrote: ‚Äú[i]if you run a business, or maintain a city, or plan power plants or highways or bridges, you‚Äôd like to know how bad things are, and how bad they‚Äôre going 1 Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC), ‚ÄúRisk Management: ‚ÄúPrinciples for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks; Request for Feedback,‚Äù OCC Bulletin 2021-62, December 16, 2021, Risk Management: Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks; Request for Feedback | OCC (treas.gov). 2 Jupiter supports the risk assessments and resiliency investments of some of our country‚Äôs largest corporations in energy, asset management, banking, insurance, and a host of other sectors, as well as the U.S. Air Force, U.S. Army, the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA), the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), and public sector customers in Florida and New York.
to get,‚Äù3 then this type of tool that incorporates climate change into its catastrophic risk modeling and disseminates easily-digestible data to public decision makers and those in the critical infrastructure sectors is essential. Jupiter is responding to some, but not all, of the questions posed in the Request for Feedback. Introduction and Overarching Comments At the outset, Jupiter would like to strongly recommend that these issues be viewed in the context that the most unlikely events can have the biggest economic impacts. This occurred in the global financial crisis of 2008 and the COVID-19 pandemic of 2020, neither of which were appropriately factored into risk management practices globally, and, both of which drove enormous tax-payer expenses to stabilize a battered economy. Often, the worst impacts of any event can be the result of a combination of several unlikely, uncorrelated drivers. Jupiter has consistently recommended that the Federal government require consideration of future conditions for any financial or physical asset it owns, subsidizes, regulates, or otherwise supports. In particular, there is a duration mismatch problem between the economic life of assets and portfolios, and the risk management practices of both the Federal government and the private sector. Current year risk is simply not a suitable proxy for future risk in a large number of economically-sensitive sectors and locations. According to the CFTC‚Äôs 2020 report ‚ÄúManaging Climate Risk in the U.S. Financial System,‚Äù and many other similar reports in the U.S. and globally, climate change already is threatening ‚Äúthe stability of the U.S. financial system‚Äù and nearly every critical infrastructure sector.4 Jupiter was founded in 2017, three years prior to the CFTC report, because it was already clear that weather-related physical risks were not well understood or acted upon, and that the impacts of extreme weather events were, and are, increasing in frequency and severity over time. Jupiter‚Äôs findings on flooding and other perils show ‚Äúa significant underestimation of risk by insurers and financial institutions that pose a potential economic calamity.‚Äù5 The fiduciary responsibility of lending institutions requires action on climate-related financial risks. As the OCC finalizes these ‚ÄúPrinciples for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks,‚Äù Jupiter encourages the OCC to consider the following recommendations: ‚Ä¢ Do not allow buyers of models to ‚Äúmodel shop,‚Äù because doing so has led to an underestimating of risk, as occurred prior to the global financial crisis and is widely viewed as a contributing factor to it. Catastrophic problems caused by ‚Äúmodel shopping‚Äù 3 Rogers, Adam, ‚ÄúCompanies Can Predict Climate Catastrophes for You ‚Äì as a Service,‚Äù WIRED Magazine, April 29, 2019. 4 Commodity Futures Trading Commission‚Äôs (CFTC) Climate-Related Market Risk Subcommittee of the Market Risk Advisory Committee, ‚ÄúManaging Climate Risk in the U.S. Financial System,‚Äù September 2020. 5 Jupiter Intelligence, ‚ÄúBanking & Insurance Special Report: A Deluge of Risk...and a Looming Crisis,‚Äù prepared for Miami-Dade County, Florida, January 2020. 2
are described in a Brookings Institution report, Origins of the Financial Crisis, as follows: ‚Äúrating agencies essentially acted as proxies for regulators; indeed, an office as high as the U.S. Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, which regulates nationally chartered banks, depended on rating agencies to assess CDO quality. . . . Since the agencies were receiving substantial payments for this service, it created a clear conflict of interest.‚Äù6 ‚Ä¢ Establish a common set of scenarios, time horizons, approaches to probabilistic distributions, and metrics. Doing so would enable companies to better assess and manage changes in risk over o time. Such commonality also would facilitate and accelerate more consistent and useful comparisons among companies within a given industry or sector. Because economic impacts differ across industry sectors, comparisons within sectors will be much easier than across sectors. For example, understanding material risks from mortgage defaults, losses from property and casualty or business interruption insurance, and service interruptions in power, health care, and even national security require different metrics. As deemed prudent, the OCC‚Äôs Principles can begin as recommendations and can o phase in over time to become increasingly robust or stringent. Consider beginning with the largest 10-20 systemically-important financial o institutions, and expanding the number of institutions over time, and increasing the rigor of the Principles over time. Also, clearly communicate the anticipated evolution in scope and substance to facilitate planning among the affected organizations. Recognize that both the science and the policy assumptions are evolving. o ‚Ä¢ Harmonize domestic and global standards to the greatest extent practicable, so that affected U.S.-based multinational companies do not have to comply with multiple, differing standards at home versus in other parts of the world. ‚Ä¢ Encourage public sector entities to use risk management modeling comparable to the high-quality data analytics that already are being adopted by industry. ‚Ä¢ Assess physical and transition risks in an integrated manner, with standardized, common climate input data sources, to more effectively account for, correlate, and address the combined effects of these risks on financial stability. Require regulated entities to align assumptions for physical and transition risk, for example, assuming low transition risk, i.e., few policy changes and business as usual will more likely result in high physical risk (i.e., experiencing more extreme events and the impacts thereof). ‚Ä¢ Use current and future-looking, rather than only historic, data. Jupiter encourages the OCC principles to facilitate the use of current and future-looking, rather than historic, data and modeling approaches for climate-related risk management. More specifically, encourage the rapid transition from existing, backward-looking model systems ‚Äì that are often decades old in their assumptions and data sources ‚Äì to the latest generation of modeling approaches that employ new data types, and inexpensive, cloud- based, high-performance computing that are readily available and established throughout the private sector. 6 Baily, Martin Neil, et. al., Origins of the Financial Crisis, Brookings Institution‚Äôs Initiative on Business and Public Policy, November 2008, page 32, https://www.brookings.edu/wp- content/uploads/2016/06/11_origins_crisis_baily_litan.pdf. 3
‚Ä¢ Recognize that uncertainty is an inherent part of planning and risk management processes; understanding and managing uncertainty is a core capability of sophisticated organizations‚Äô established risk management processes. Climate-related data and derived metrics need to be clear, transparent, and easy to measure, monitor, assess, verify, and report. The following elements are critical to establishing sound data and quality metrics and models: ‚Ä¢ A consistent and global methodology to derive granular climate metrics. A patchwork of information based on different models, regional models, and differing o methods creates ambiguity and obscures uncertainty. ‚Ä¢ Methods for quantifying and accounting for some of the aforementioned uncertainty as well as for systematic errors (i.e., bias). Down-scaled data, so that the spatial resolution is appropriately suited to the peril or o hazard being considered. ‚Ä¢ Current and future-looking data modeled in such a way as to account for changes in the timing and severity of extreme events (e.g., what was a 1-in-100 year storm that now occurs once every 10 or 20 years). Recognize that the most damaging and extreme weather events can affect the tails of statistical distributions. Given the rapid pace and nature of change in the severity of extreme weather events, historic-looking data or models are inadequate. Consider that often the worst impacts are the result of a combination of several o unlikely, uncorrelated drivers, and that on a risk weighted basis, the most unlikely events can have the biggest economic impacts, similar to what occurred in the global financial crisis of 2008 and the COVID-19 pandemic of 2020, neither of which was appropriately factored into risk management practices globally, and both of which drove enormous taxpayer expenses to stabilize a battered economy. Data should be drawn from the most recent and well-populated climate projections o and based on the best verified science. While traditional catastrophe models (cat models) have formed the backbone of well- o managed underwriting for insurance and re-insurance of natural disaster risks for nearly 30 years, these models are not designed and are inadequate for climate risk management.7 Decision makers and industry sector representatives increasingly recognize the importance of using current and forward-looking data in climate-related risk analyses. ‚Ä¢ Assumptions in, and limitations of, metrics that are based on established global climate models (GCMs) should be clear and transparent. Such assumptions, inputs, and outputs, must be transparent and well-documented to help decision-makers explain consequent analyses and conclusions, even if confidentially disclosed to regulators and industry. Climate models have performed quite accurately for well over a decade and have o generally improved over time. However, like other models, climate models are not always 100 percent accurate. They can contain imperfections in their underlying assumptions and their ability to forecast, just like all other models, including those that use common macroeconomic assumptions to predict GDP growth and interest rates. 7 As an example, see: https://medium.com/jupiterintel/cat-models-f0fc7e890bef. 4
‚Ä¢ Climate scenarios (e.g., Shared Socioeconomic Pathways) will evolve over time ‚Äì and can influence policy development and risk management planning processes ‚Äì as scientific knowledge evolves. Imperfections in underlying assumptions and the constantly-evolving state of o scientific understanding will continue to occur. At times, this can result in the creation of extremes in climate projections that predict warming beyond realistic physical reality, as happened in the most recent Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) models and was, in practice, rejected by the scientific community. Some models previously underestimated the amount of anticipated warming and associated physical impacts. For example, while the Paris Agreement set an increase in temperature of 2 degrees C as the agreed-upon global target, it, and subsequent scientific reports (i.e., IPCC), acknowledged a temperature increase of 1.5 degrees C would be preferable. As a result, the assumption that 1.5 degrees C warming was the likely scenario became the prevailing view for several subsequent years. However, an increase of 2 degrees C is now considered the best-case (i.e., not the likely) scenario. Banking regulators in other countries assume a best case of temperatures rising by 2 degrees C (i.e., 1.5 degrees C is no longer a plausible scenario). And, more recent scientific updates have led to worst-case scenarios that the world will warm by at least 4.5 degrees C by 2100.8 Complying with these criteria would help banks improve their management of climate-related financial risks. As noted in a May 2021 Executive Order on Climate-Related Financial Risk, ‚Äúthe failure of financial institutions to appropriately and adequately account for and measure these physical and transition risks threatens the competitiveness of U.S. companies and markets, the life savings and pensions of U.S. workers and families, and the ability of U.S. financial institutions to serve communities.‚Äù9 8 Holtz, Robert Lee, ‚ÄúClimate Scientists Encounter Limits of Computer Models, Bedeviling Policy,‚Äù Wall Street Journal (WSJ), February 6, 2022, https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-change-global-warming-computer-model- 11642191155?mod=djm_dailydiscvrtst; Sorkin, Rich, CEO of Jupiter Intelligence, LinkedIn commentary on WSJ article, Febru ary 7, 2022, Rich Sorkin on LinkedIn: Climate Scientists Encounter Limits of Computer Models, Bedeviling. 9 The White House, ‚ÄúExecutive Order on Climate-Related Financial Risk,‚Äù May 2021, https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/presidential-actions/2021/05/20/executive-order-on-climate-related- financial-risk/. 5
OCC Questions for Consideration Applicability 1. Are there additional categories of banks (i.e., based on asset size, location, business model) to which these principles should apply? As noted earlier, Jupiter recommends beginning with the largest 10-20 systemically-important financial institutions, then expanding the number of institutions and the rigor of the principles over time, clearly communicating the planned evolution to facilitate planning among the impacted organizations. Jupiter encourages the OCC‚Äôs principles to account for correlated risk, including supply chain risk, affecting a large portion of any bank‚Äôs overall portfolio. Tailoring 2. How could future guidance assist a bank in developing its climate-related financial risk management practices commensurate to its size, complexity, risk profile, and scope of operations? Given that climate change poses major risks to the stability of the U.S. financial system and its institutions, future OCC guidance could help banks better manage and adapt to climate-related financial risks. The OCC‚Äôs focus on large banks in these proposed Principles is appropriate, given that larger institutions have more human and technical resources as well as larger budgets to enhance their financial climate-related risk management procedures or practices. Jupiter commends the OCC for adopting this approach of addressing large banks first. Such guidance could help a bank develop its climate-related risk management practices in a manner that is commensurate with its risk profile. To maximize the effectiveness of these anticipated Principles, Jupiter encourages the OCC to provide a roadmap to banks, with clear expectations of how the Principles and any associated standards will evolve over time, as banks work to meet such emerging standards The OCC should also consider ensuring sufficient rigor and commonality to facilitate uniform, consistent evaluations and comparisons of climate-related data, models and analytics, scenarios, and time horizons. In addition, such standards, of course, should be based on sound, peer-reviewed climate science. Please see the Introduction to this document for more detailed recommendations that Jupiter encourages the OCC to consider, as it proceeds to develop guidance pertaining to climate-related data models, and analytics, that will be used by large banks. 6
General 3. What challenges do banks face in incorporating these principles into their risk management systems? How should the OCC further engage with banks to understand those challenges? Climate-related financial risks are an emerging threat to financial stability that only recently are being incorporated into corporate governance and risk management practices. The expertise needed to evaluate climate-related data differs from that applied to traditional financial risk management and the evaluation of financial risks. Few banks currently employ climate scientists or other technical experts with sufficient background to effectively and efficiently evaluate relevant data or any downstream models into which such data might be incorporated. Moreover, in some cases, the currently-available data is insufficient to model the extreme perils that are or will be material. Among the most sophisticated and forward-looking banks, capacity building to address these challenges with skilled labor is already far along, and the OCC should encourage banks that might not yet be as far along to build capacity to incorporate these principles into their risk management systems. The OCC can help by ensuring that any guidance or principles it issues contain clear, easily- understood standards for banks to use in evaluating climate-related data, analytics, and data products and in comparing climate-related financial risk among banks. Jupiter offers some suggestions for such standards, at least for potential initial consideration, in the Introduction above. With transparently and easily understood standards in place, large banks will feel increasingly comfortable in evaluating climate-related data products. Such standards and processes also will expedite the adaptation and resilience of our financial system to climate-related risks and will enhance banks‚Äô management thereof. Current Risk Management Practices 4. What specific tools or strategies have banks used to successfully incorporate climate-related financial risks into their risk management frameworks? As of this submission, one-half of the U.S.‚Äôs largest banks and government-sponsored enterprises subscribe to Jupiter‚Äôs climate analytics services, including what is apparently the most advanced and sophisticated implementation to date, with over 60 million locations assessed. The majority of banks and lenders are just beginning their processes for determining ways to achieve sound and effective climate-related financial risk management. As noted in the Introduction and throughout this document, when banks are able to select a standardized set of scenarios, time horizons, and probabilistic determinations, as part of incorporating climate- related financial risks into their risk management frameworks, their success in managing climate- related financial risk and overall risk improves. 7
In addition, banks sometimes use ‚Äúfirst-pass‚Äù attempts to assess risk management. They are building on this approach, by incorporating climate-conditioned input data into existing legacy model systems. For example, the projection of the Loan-to-Value (LTV) ratio for home mortgages can be adjusted to reflect climate risks and then incorporated into existing mortgage probability of default (PD) models. This approach is both better than the prior approach and deeply flawed, and is usually the result of required haste in adjusting risk management practices. The OCC should strongly consider encouraging banks, lenders, and supervisors to rapidly transition to the latest generation of services using ground-up modeling approaches that account for the changing nature and inter-relationship of physical and transition risks into the future. Just as today‚Äôs Comprehensive Capital Analysis and Review (CCAR) stress testing regimes bear little resemblance to those initially deployed over a decade ago, Jupiter expects climate risk management to evolve in complexity, and in the understanding thereof, over time. OCC‚Äôs guidance should be consistent with this anticipated evolution. 5. How do banks determine when climate-related financial risks are material and warrant greater than routine attention by the board and management? No response to this question. 6. What time horizon do banks consider relevant when identifying and assessing the materiality of climate-related financial risks? Generally speaking, banks approach this in one of two ways: a prudent internal risk management approach provides banks with quality information regarding what time horizons are relevant for specific business units, use cases, and asset types to avoid material duration mismatch problems. More commonly, banks are waiting for clear regulatory guidance on what areas are subject to scrutiny and the relevant time horizons. Absent guidance on time horizons, some banks will make a simple assumption using the shortest time horizon they can justify, and underestimate risk during the duration of the portfolio. While location-specific geography and other factors can be case-specific, standards for enabling choice of time horizon(s), risk tolerance, and climate scenarios are extremely important to ensure consistency of information across and within regulated entities ‚Äì within a given sector. It is important to emphasize that these timeframes should not be limited by excessive discounts that subject future generations to undue costs, due to present inadequate risk management. Climate risk is unique among financial risks in terms of the ongoing, repeated, and growing, nature of climate impacts from extreme weather events. The life of a particular asset (e.g., a 30-year mortgage) cannot be the only criterion used when assessing the relevant time horizons and discount rate needed for climate-related financial risk management. 8
7. What, if any, specific products, practices, and strategies‚Äìfor example, insurance or derivatives contracts or other capital market instruments‚Äìdo banks use to hedge, transfer, or mitigate climate-related financial risks? The use of any products, practices, or strategies to hedge, transfer, or mitigate climate-related financial risk is extremely limited and embryonic, especially when compared to the use of reinsurance to transfer credit risk, as pioneered by the GSEs, AON and others. 8. What, if any, climate-related financial products or services‚Äìfor example, ‚Äúgreen bonds,‚Äù derivatives, dedicated investment funds, or other instruments that take climate-related considerations into account‚Äìdo banks offer to clients and customers? What risks, if any, do these products or services pose? No response to this question. 9. How do banks currently consider the impacts of climate-related financial risk mitigation strategies and financial products on households and communities, specifically LMI and other disadvantaged communities? To a very large extent, without other off-setting policies, LMI and other populations are and will be disproportionately impacted by climate change, because they tend to live in areas vulnerable to extreme weather events and climate change. If banks perceive increased physical risk in these areas, they could cease to lend money there, as reportedly has occurred in some instances. As banks reduce their risk, the risks to households and communities increases, because they could suffer the double impact of being trapped in increasingly vulnerable areas, while suffering negative economic consequences, including potentially the loss or degradation of their homes, and/or the collateral risk of depreciated property, unless they obtain federal, state, or local public financial assistance. This is an important issue on which Jupiter is already working with some large lenders to ameliorate, through its ‚ÄúJupiter Promise‚Äù program for under-served communities. Data, Disclosures, and Reporting 10. What, if any, specific climate-related data, metrics, tools, and models from borrowers and other counterparties do banks need to identify, measure, monitor, and control their own climate-related financial risks? How do banks currently obtain this information? What gaps and other concerns are there with respect to these data, metrics, tools, or models? Presumably, banks need a uniform and consistent set of data, metrics, tools, and models to identify, measure, monitor, and control their own climate-related financial risks. As the OCC advances these Principles, the recommended standardized approach herein would facilitate these consistencies and enhanced capabilities, including the ability to make comparisons across banks. 9
Location-Specific Data is Key to Effective Management of Physical Climate Risks Physical climate risk is inherently a placed-based risk. The effective management of physical climate risk requires detailed knowledge of the location of all physical assets. Such information has always been required for mortgage lending. Yet, for counter-party lending, the same focus on physical assets has not been a traditional part of effective risk management. Jupiter encourages OCC guidance to recommend the availability of granular, rooftop-level information for all relevant physical assets and that banks then incorporate this information into their modeled risk assessments. Similarly, the supply chain of any counter-party borrower should be assessed for risk, based on the exposure of its capital infrastructure to climate risks. Eventually, it might be necessary to disclose and track the latitude and longitude of all placed-based assets affecting a company‚Äôs operations. While such information might be hard to acquire today, the location of physical assets will be vital to understanding an entity's physical risk exposure. 11. How could existing regulatory reporting requirements be augmented to better capture banks‚Äô exposure to climate-related financial risks? Jupiter encourages the OCC, as it proceeds with these Principles, to consider ways to make them consistent with other relevant requirements, such as anticipated Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) climate risk disclosure requirements, to the extent practicable ‚Äì recognizing the latter are not within the OCC‚Äôs jurisdiction.10 In addition, while providing flexibility to banks, uniformity of data, scenarios, time horizons, and so forth will facilitate more consistent information and comparisons across banks. Harmonization of standards globally will also help and is important for these reasons. In turn, such an approach would better capture banks‚Äô exposure and resulting reporting requirements. Scenario Analysis 12. Scenario analysis is an important component of climate risk management that requires assumptions about plausible future states of the world. How do banks use climate scenario models, analysis, or tools and what challenges do they face? As of this submission, one-half of the U.S.‚Äôs largest banks and government sponsored enterprises subscribe to Jupiter‚Äôs climate analytics services, including what apparently is the most advanced and sophisticated implementation to date, with over 60 million locations assessed. 10 Jupiter has been encouraging the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) to require climate-related risk disclosure, beginning with large companies and, ultimately, considering a phased approach to expanding such requirements. 10
The most sophisticated banks already have sophisticated in-house staff to incorporate these types of analytics into their existing risk and model risk management practices and are underway, with the biggest challenges being implementation and refinement at scale. Other banks are still building capacity to even properly evaluate their alternatives, while some simply resist the need for this type of risk management as an enterprise solution. 13. What factors are most salient for the OCC to consider when designing and executing scenario analysis exercises? As the OCC proceeds with these Principles, Jupiter encourages it to consider the following criteria (as also reflected in the Introduction above). ‚Ä¢ Establish a common set of scenarios, time horizons, approach to probabilistic distributions, acceptable risk levels, and metrics. ‚Ä¢ Harmonize U.S. principles with global standards, to the greatest extent practicable. Jupiter encourages the OCC to issue guidance that adopts a rigorous approach to o climate data validation that is better tailored to a consistent and global approach than those currently advocated by the Bank of England. ‚Ä¢ As the OCC issues principles, consider facilitating an integrated framework for physical and transition risk management including by: Incorporate physical and transition risk feedback loops into scenario-based analyses; o and, Align analyses with the Task Force and Climate Related Financial Disclosures o (TCFD) pillars.11 ‚Ä¢ Use current and future-looking, rather than only historic, data. ‚Ä¢ Avoid a one-size-fits-all approach to assessing risk across industry sectors or use cases. ‚Ä¢ Ensure analyses are sector- as well as location-specific. When assessing material climate-related financial risk exposure, having data that is as granular as possible is vital. Regional climate peril indices that aggregate information can be useful for a quick visualization and assessment of risks, and for decision making, when materiality is low, but can mask important variations that significantly impact more material risks. Jupiter encourages the OCC in its forthcoming guidance to consider including a recommendation that banks use caution, when solely using aggregate regional or visual analyses to manage climate-related risks. One reason such a caution is important is that climate-related physical risks, like floods and extreme heat, vary tremendously over land surfaces and geographies. Averaging such risk(s) over large regions can lead to 11 University of Cambridge Institute for Sustainability Leadership (CISL)‚Äôs ClimateWise, ‚ÄúClimate Tango: Principles for integrating physical and transition climate-risk assessment with sectoral examples,‚Äù January 13, 2022, https://www.cisl.cam.ac.uk/resources/publications/climate-tango-principles-integrating-physical-and-transition- climate-risk. 11
attenuation biases in the results12 and, consequently, to erroneous conclusions about the nature and materiality of climate-related physical risks. ‚Ä¢ Make risk management modeling available to public sector entities using high-quality data analytics that are comparable to those already being used by industry; The OCC should ensure high-quality input data sources are available globally (e.g., Global Climate Models, Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) data/models). Regional Climate Models (RCMs), while useful in certain instances, may not apply globally. While using global input data is important, it also is important to produce and use more granular data and data analytics outputs. For (more) material risks, granular (e.g., asset- level) data is especially important. Implementing both of these approaches will facilitate enhanced consistency in terms of methodology and ability to make comparisons among banks. Jupiter encourages the OCC to consider recommending that banks provide documentation regarding the assumptions and limitations about the selected input climate data and their impact on downstream models and data products. Conclusion Over the last five years, awareness of the importance of climate-related financial risk management has grown dramatically. The availability of data, derived metrics, and services to facilitate climate-related risk management has matured during the same period, while costs have declined significantly, as well. The OCC‚Äôs Principles will further help large banks undertake more robust climate risk management. Other considerations beyond Return on Investment (ROI), including shareholder expectations and regulatory compliance, also merit consideration. As the OCC advances these Principles, it should consider ensuring flexibility to banks, yet should also consider enhancing the ability to better manage climate-related financial risk and make better comparisons across banks, by facilitating standardized, uniform, consistent choices of climate scenarios (e.g., best, worst, or most likely), time horizons, and approach to probabilistic distributions. Modeling climate risk management necessitates the use of consistent, high-quality data and analytics, and this includes yielding location-specific, granular data. Global harmonization among domestic and international standards would reduce compliance burdens, including costs, complexity, and more. That said, across industrial sectors, a one-size-fits-all approach is not ideal and, therefore, is recommended to be avoided. 12 Hsiang, Solomon, Climate Econometrics, Annual Review of Resource Economics (2016), 8:1, 43-75. 12
The current state of the science behind physical risk prediction is more than sufficient to support an integrated assessment of both physical and transition risks. Jupiter encourages the OCC to signal to banks that the banks should anticipate that OCC will be recommending an integrated approach to modeling physical and transition risks. Lastly, Jupiter strongly emphasizes that during the last fifteen years, the U.S. economy has been battered twice by problems that were not adequately modeled or planned for, in both cases ‚Äì the Global Financial Crisis and the COVID-19 pandemic ‚Äì at enormous costs to U.S. taxpayers. Within this context, ‚Äúbad actors‚Äù abused the public trust, with billions of dollars in fines paid by S&P and Moody‚Äôs for having sold biased model results. Similarly, entities whose economics are driven by Assets Under Management have already engaged in practices designed to convince investors that they were responsible stewards of the economy, while essentially engaging in business as usual. It is critical that the OCC consider the economic motivations and past history of suppliers in the market, when choosing whose data may be reliable for internal and external purposes. Jupiter again appreciates the opportunity to provide this feedback and stands ready to serve as a resource to the OCC, including by offering technical assistance. Sincerely, Rich Sorkin CEO Jupiter Intelligence 13","Jupiter Intelligence, a leader in climate risk prediction, comments on the OCC's draft principles for climate-related financial risk management for large banks. They emphasize the importance of using advanced climate analytics to manage risks from extreme weather events. Jupiter recommends that the OCC establish common scenarios, time horizons, and metrics to improve risk management and facilitate comparisons across banks. They caution against ""model shopping"" and stress the need for harmonized domestic and global standards. Jupiter highlights the importance of using current and future-looking data rather than historical data and suggests that banks should incorporate granular, location-specific data into their risk assessments. They also advocate for integrating physical and transition risks in scenario analyses. Jupiter warns of the economic impacts of not adequately modeling risks, drawing parallels to the 2008 financial crisis and the COVID-19 pandemic. They offer their expertise to assist the OCC in developing robust climate risk management principles."
kzo-frr9-2uk9,"OCC: Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks STRICTLY PRIVATE AND CONFIDENTIAL February 14, 2022 Ms. Crystal Cook Examiner-In-Charge Office of the Comptroller of the Currency 350 S. Grand Avenue, 11th Floor Los Angeles, CA 90071 Re: Request for Feedback on Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks (Docket ID OCC-2021-0023) Dear Ms. Cook: City National Bank (CNB) submits this letter in response to the request for public feedback on the ‚ÄúPrinciples for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks‚Äù (Draft Principles) issued by the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) on December 16, 2021 (Request for Feedback).1 We welcome the OCC‚Äôs plans to release future guidance on climate-related financial risk management, and appreciate the opportunity to comment on the Draft Principles. We look forward to engaging in further conversations on this topic with you, and are enthusiastic about a principles-based and regulatory consistent climate risk guidance. I. Are there additional categories of banks (i.e., based on asset size, location, business model) to which these principles should apply? Banks with a business model, operating environment, or risk profile, regardless of size, which are concentrated in a market, industry, sector, or geographic area that is exposed to material physical and transition risks. Consideration should also be given to the size of the bank within the OCC Large Bank Supervision segment. II. How could future guidance assist a bank in developing its climate-related financial risk management practices commensurate to its size, complexity, risk profile, and scope of operations? 1. Provide clear guidance on the required or recommended reporting and disclosure frameworks (e.g. TCFD). 2. Provide guidance on approach to climate risk. Is it trying to measure impact of natural disaster on safety and soundness of Banks, or is it trying to regulate Banks‚Äô and Clients‚Äô carbon footprint, or both? 3. Provide guidance for meaningful stress test scenarios based on operational geography. 4. Provide guidance on analyzing internal data, and climate-related portfolio analysis techniques. 5. Provide guidance on mitigating impacts to households and communities, specifically LMI and other disadvantaged communities, resulting from climate-related financial risks. 6. Provide clear expectations as it relates to client data analysis for banks whose clientele is primarily comprised of non-public borrowers ‚Äì i.e. less sophisticated financial reporting from the clients 1 OCC, Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks (Dec. 16, 2021).
OCC: Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks III. What challenges do banks face in incorporating these principles into their risk management systems? How should the OCC further engage with banks to understand those challenges? 1. Challenges with getting proper, labeled data both internal and external datasets. 2. Challenges with raising awareness of the importance for managing financial climate risk. 3. Horizontal practices (peer review data), data aggregated by bank asset size, including within the Large Bank segment. 4. Determining which clients of the Bank are large enough and/or in a position to effectively manage and report on climate related risks. IV. What specific tools or strategies have banks used to successfully incorporate climate-related financial risks into their risk management frameworks? None currently. The bank continues to evaluate specific tools and strategies for incorporating climate-related financial risks into risk policies and frameworks. V. How do banks determine when climate-related financial risks are material and warrant greater than routine attention by the board and management? Under development. The bank continues to evaluate factors that will determine climate-related risk materiality. VI. What time horizon do banks consider relevant when identifying and assessing the materiality of climate- related financial risks? Some risks are considered in the short to medium term (1-3 years), such as reputation risk, extreme weather events, and public policy decisions. Other risks are considered over a longer time horizon (3+ years), such as sector and geographic concentrations, demographic changes, operational resiliency, and geopolitical trends. Climate-related credit risks are considered on a time horizon commensurate with the tenor and collateral of the underwriting. VII. What, if any, specific products, practices, and strategies‚Äìfor example, insurance or derivatives contracts or other capital market instruments‚Äìdo banks use to hedge, transfer, or mitigate climate-related financial risks? CNB does not currently use specific products to hedge, transfer, or mitigate climate-related financial risks outside of standard insurance (e.g. flood insurance for mortgage and CRE). VIII. What, if any, climate-related financial products or services‚Äìfor example, ‚Äúgreen bonds,‚Äù derivatives, dedicated investment funds, or other instruments that take climate-related considerations into account‚Äì do banks offer to clients and customers?4 What risks, if any, do these products or services pose? 1. CNB does not currently offer green-products. 2. These products contain risks related to accurately pricing future climate impacts from both physical and transition perspectives. IX. How do banks currently consider the impacts of climate-related financial risk mitigation strategies and financial products on households and communities, specifically LMI and other disadvantaged communities? The bank continues to evaluate how to best consider and mitigate the impacts on LMI and disadvantaged communities resulting from climate-related financial risks.
OCC: Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks X. What, if any, specific climate-related data, metrics, tools, and models from borrowers and other counterparties do banks need to identify, measure, monitor, and control their own climate-related financial risks? How do banks currently obtain this information? What gaps and other concerns are there with respect to these data, metrics, tools, or models? 1. Banks need internal and external historical datasets, especially for private companies who are not subject to public reporting and do not have this information readily available, whether for themselves or for their clients. 2. Banks can currently obtain this information through third party data providers (ClimateWise, Moody‚Äôs ESG Solutions, Blackrock‚Äôs Aladdin), peer data aggregators (Moody‚Äôs), and internal data lakes. 3. These datasets are generally incomplete and often rely on black-box models for generating output. XI. How could existing regulatory reporting requirements be augmented to better capture banks‚Äô exposure to climate-related financial risks? 1. Incorporate a light set of requirements within OCC Heightened Standards to ensure raised awareness, and to begin the process of building a Climate Risk Management program. 2. Regulatory reporting requirements should scale with the size, clientele, and complexity of the bank. XII. Scenario analysis is an important component of climate risk management that requires assumptions about plausible future states of the world. How do banks use climate scenario models, analysis, or tools and what challenges do they face? 1. The bank uses scenario analysis in its capital planning activities. 2. Challenges faced during climate risk scenario analysis include: a. Lack of clarity of expectations b. Data challenges c. Choosing appropriate scenarios and methodology d. Technical challenges in assessing impact (e.g. timescales, level of granularity, etc.) e. Limited local expertise f. Identifying opportunities, not just risks g. Usefulness for informing business strategy h. Resourcing and expertise XIII. What factors are most salient for the OCC to consider when designing and executing scenario analysis exercises? 1. Size and complexity of the bank, and whether or not it is subject to CCAR 2. Availability of data. 3. Client willingness and ability to provide (i.e. small businesses) 4. Climate risk data vendor best practices 5. Analytics, scenario, and methodology best practices 6. Data strategy and governance 7. Creating long term strategies to transition ad-hoc analysis to BAU We believe that the Draft Principles are appropriately high-level and that final guidance reflecting this approach would be helpful and effective. We urge the OCC to scale any future regulatory reporting requirements with the size, clientele, and complexity of the banks, and to provide clear guidance for expectations to client data analysis of non-
OCC: Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks public borrowers or borrowers with less sophisticated reporting. We look forward to participating in this evolving process. We appreciate your interest in our comments and welcome the opportunity to discuss our feedback and any specific concerns. Sincerely, Marcelo Brutti EVP, Chief Risk Officer Cc: Ms. Kelly Coffey, Chief Executive Officer Mr. John Bai, Chief Financial Officer Mr. Michael Speaker, Chief Compliance Officer Ms. Laura Lee, Regulatory Relations Ms. Dana Moore, Risk & Regulatory Liaison Mr. Tim J. Grob, Head of U.S. Regulatory Relations","City National Bank (CNB) responds to the OCC's request for feedback on climate-related financial risk management principles for large banks. CNB supports the OCC's initiative and suggests that the principles should apply to banks of all sizes with significant exposure to climate risks. They recommend clear guidance on reporting frameworks, stress test scenarios, and data analysis techniques. CNB highlights challenges such as data acquisition, awareness, and client engagement. They note the absence of specific tools for managing climate risks and the ongoing development of risk materiality assessments. CNB does not currently offer green products but acknowledges the risks associated with them. They emphasize the need for regulatory requirements to scale with bank size and complexity and call for clear expectations for client data analysis. CNB uses scenario analysis in capital planning but faces challenges like data clarity and technical expertise. They advocate for high-level guidance and scalable regulatory requirements, expressing willingness to engage further with the OCC on these issues."
kzp-ov4c-r43y,"February 14, 2022 Michael J. Hsu Acting Comptroller of the Currency 400 7th St. SW Washington, DC 20219 Re: Docket ID OCC-2021-0023, OCC Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Dear Acting Comptroller Hsu, On behalf of the82undersigned organizations andour millions of members and supporters, we welcome the opportunity to comment on the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency‚Äôs (OCC‚Äôs) Principles for Climate-Related Financial Risk Management for Large Banks. We support this important step toward advancing banks‚Äô efforts to assess and address climate-related risk, and we urge the OCC to strengthen and finalize the draft as soon as possible. Climate change poses significant risks to the safety and soundness of banks, the financial system, and communities. We support the OCC‚Äôs recommendations for big banks to take a whole-of-business approach to mitigating climate risk, to consider longer time horizons for assessing and addressing climate risk, and to develop climate-related data and scenario analysis modeling. Two elements of particular importance include directing banks to align their internal strategies with their public climate commitments, and recognizing fair lending implications and the adverse effect that risk-management measures could have on low-income and other disadvantaged households and communities. Ensuring transparency and alignment of climate commitments and strategies We welcome the provision directing banks to ensure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public climate commitments. Public statements, like recent commitments made by banks to create and execute ‚Äúnet-zero‚Äù transition plans, are a reflection of management‚Äôs strategic vision for the company and an important part of climate risk management. To be consistent with its public commitments, a bank‚Äôs corresponding actions and internal strategies must be grounded in climate science and technological realities. Recently, nine US banks have made commitments to ‚Äúnet-zero‚Äù emissions by 2050, consistent with the Paris Agreement‚Äôs goal of limiting global average temperature rise to 1.5¬∞C, as members of the bank-led Net-Zero Banking Alliance (NZBA) initiative under the Glasgow Financial Alliance for Net Zero (GFANZ).
However, these banks are falling short of establishing strategies to meet these commitments and are still engaging in actions inconsistent with them. Many continue to finance new fossil fuel and other high-emitting projects or companies expanding their high-emitting activities. These activities are not compatible with reaching net-zero emissions by 2050 or limiting global temperature rise to 1.5¬∞C. This conduct raises questions about whether bank managers desire to follow through on these commitments‚Äìand are failing to do so‚Äìor are merely seeking public relations wins. The OCC should clarify banks‚Äô understanding of how the agency will consider the relationship between transition plans and internal strategies. Among the most significant parameters to expand on are (1) aligning financing for activities, projects, and companies that drive greenhouse gas pollution with the bank‚Äôs own commitments; (2) providing measurable near term targets based firmly in climate science and technological realities; (3) and accurately accounting for the challenges posed by offsets. Robust transition plans are important not only to ensure that banks‚Äô internal strategies are consistent with public statements, but also because planning for a transition away from greenhouse gas emissions is important for the safety and soundness of all banks, large and small, and for fair access of marginalized communities to financial services. While some banks, such as Amalgamated Bank, have aligned their climate commitments to science and understand the need to reduce risks for both it and the financial system, other banks need additional guidance from the OCC. Linking Emissions Reductions Targets and Financing Activity Fossil fuel expansion is not compatible with any science-based limit on global temperature rise or with meeting public commitments for net-zero financed emissions by 2050. Key tenets of the International Energy Agency‚Äôsroadmap for achievingnet-zero emissions by 2050include ‚Äúno investmentin new fossil fuel supply projects‚Äùand‚Äúno further final investment decisions for new unabated coal plants.‚ÄùYet U.S. banks, includingJPMorgan Chase, Citi, Wells Fargo, and Bank of America, are the most significant financiers of fossil fuels globally and have continued to increase their funding despite voicing their support for the Paris Agreement and committing to net zero by 2050.Citirecently committed to a29% reduction in absolute emissions from its energy sector financing by 2030, yet the bank failed to provide a plan to stop funding fossil fuel expansion to align with its net-zero pledge. More troublingly, major banks such asJPMorgan Chase,Morgan Stanley, andGoldman Sachshave setinterim targets based on convoluted financed emissions intensity metrics that are difficult to compare and do not conform with the
reduction in absolute emissions that is necessary to achieve net zero by 2050. These contradictions raise serious questions about the sincerity of banks‚Äô climate commitments or, alternatively, the soundness of their management processes and controls. To meaningfully align their business with their commitments, banks need to follow a science based approach to meeting absolute emissions reduction targets. Measurable Targets The OCC should make clear that banks committing to net zero by 2050 must have in place, and must implement, credible internal strategies that meet the imperatives of climate science, technological realities, and safety and soundness. A credible plan in line with public commitments includes short- and medium-term targets and metrics. Such milestones are critical not just to meeting the commitments, but also to avoiding a fire sale from banks trying to meet their commitments at the last minute. A credible plan should include milestones such as a 50% reduction in absolute financed emissions by 2030. Offsets Some banks may seek to rely heavily on purported ‚Äúoffsets‚Äù of carbon emissions from forests, wetlands, and carbon removal technologies to achieve net-zero carbon emissions. But offsets have deep limitations such that they cannot be relied on to play more than a trivial role in any credible net-zero plan. The limitations include difficultiesquantifyingorverifyingavoided or reduced emissions,questionsabout theeffectivenessandpermanenceofnatural sinksthat may bethreatenedby human or natural impacts, concernsabout the reliability andlegal normcomplianceof promised reductions due toviolationsofIndigenous rights and treaties, the lack of technologies that arecredibleanddependable,and thepotential for fraud. For these reasons,standard settersare increasingly treatingoffsets only as a last resort to negate residual emissions that remain after financial institutions have directly reduced financed emissions as near to zero as is possible. Ensuring fair access to financial services We welcome the OCC‚Äôs recognition of potential fair lending concerns as banks mitigate climate related risks. The OCC should address two key ways climate risk threatens fair access to financial services. The first is through impacts to the safety and soundness of local banks. Eighty percent of institutions supervised by the OCC are smaller banks, particularly regional,
community, and agricultural banks. Some are more vulnerable to climate risk than larger banks due to the financial needs they meet, and they are also critically important for rural communities and marginalized communities. One in five counties depends on community banks for access to a physical bank branch. The second threat is through measures taken by large banks to reduce their own exposures to credit and other financial risks. Such bank measures are likely to include closing branches in ‚Äúhot-spot‚Äù areas impacted by climate-related extreme weather events, increasing costs related to financing in these areas, and pursuing other measures that could reduce access to services. The guidance‚Äôs attention to disproportionate impacts is welcome. Banks may find that it pushes them in multiple directions. While the guidance directs banks to reduce their exposures, it also notes that some responses may be unacceptable due to disproportionate impacts to marginalized communities. The OCC should move quickly to issue additional guidance on how banks can improve on equitably providing credit to vulnerable communities while acting in a safe and sound manner. As part of this guidance, it should require that banks identify, measure, monitor, and address potential and occurring disproportionate impacts on marginalized communities, such as communities of color and low-moderate-income communities. Banks should have a system for tracking their actions to avoid or address disproportionate impacts and documenting their progress on addressing those impacts. It should also recognize that orderly reductions in financed emissions would most meaningfully reduce safety and soundness risks for all banks, large and small, as well as the risk of impaired access to financial services for all communities. Conclusion These draft principles are a historic step in the right direction. They are also a starting point that should be followed by additional guidance. The U.S. lags behind much of the world on mitigating climate-related risk. We encourage the OCC to follow the lead of global peers atthe European Central Bank (ECB),Canada‚Äôs Office of theSuperintendent of Financial Institutions, and other regulators who are actively exploring the need for additional supervisory measures to respond to climate risk, including the need for increasedattention to capital and liquidity requirementsat the largest, most complex institutions. We look forward to continuing to engage with you on these issues. For questions, please contact Anne Perrault ataperrault@citizen.organd Yevgeny Shrago at
