It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate. Be A hero AND HOLD THEIR FEET TO THE FIRE FOR CLEAN ENERGY !","The comment addresses Comptroller Hsu, urging him to take decisive action on climate change and banking practices. It criticizes banks for publicly claiming to address climate change while continuing to invest heavily in fossil fuels, which exacerbates climate risks. The commenter emphasizes the need for regulatory intervention to prevent banks from making short-term decisions that threaten the financial system, marginalized communities, and the environment. They support proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, and align internal strategies with public climate commitments. The comment calls for the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) to ensure banks' actions align with their net-zero carbon commitments and to incorporate climate risk management into supervisory ratings. The commenter urges the OCC to issue strong guidance and hold banks accountable for transitioning to clean energy."
l01-kpqd-4zzl,"Climate change is the most terrifying issue of our time. I see what‚Äôs happening around the world and I am so worried for all of us, especially young people trying to believe in a positive future. Banks are a huge part of the problem and can be a huge part of the solution, if they put people over profits. Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks.¬†Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities. I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they:‚Ä®1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business;‚Ä®2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available;‚Ä®3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits;‚Ä®4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments. The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.","The comment addresses the urgent issue of climate change, emphasizing its impact on young people and the global community. It criticizes banks for contributing to the problem by investing in fossil fuels, despite public claims of addressing climate change. The commenter thanks Comptroller Hsu for addressing this issue and urges regulators to hold banks accountable. They support proposed guidance for banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public commitments. The commenter calls for the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (OCC) to ensure banks' actions align with their net-zero carbon commitments and to factor climate risk management into supervisory ratings. They advocate for strong guidance and remedies to protect against unsafe banking practices and minimize climate risk."
l01-p079-ahp7,"Thank you, Comptroller Hsu, for taking up the issue of climate change and banks. Even as banks publicly claim to be taking climate change seriously and phasing out financing for greenhouse gas emissions, they are investing billions into companies that produce fossil fuels. Banks‚Äô continued investments in fossil fuels are driving climate change ‚Äì a crisis that puts our financial system, people of color and low-income communities, and our planet at risk. Regulators must not let financial institutions gamble with our future. We need you to push banks to take the urgent steps necessary to address the dangers they face from climate change, and stop their short-term business decisions from endangering our economy and communities.
I support the proposed guidance‚Äôs recommendations to banks that they: 1. Incorporate climate-related risk management into every level of business; 2. Plan for climate change over a long time horizon, and update models as additional data becomes available; 3. Develop clear definitions of possible climate-related risk exposures, and metrics for setting limits; 4. And make sure that their internal strategies are consistent with their public-facing climate commitments.
The OCC must ensure that banks‚Äô actions match their commitments to zeroing out their net carbon emissions. Banks‚Äô management of climate risk should be factored into their supervisory ratings, too. It is in the best interest of both the public and banks themselves to act now to minimize climate risk. The OCC must use the full extent of its authority to issue strong final guidance to banks on climate risk, continue to protect against unsafe and unsound bank practices, and require remedies from banks where appropriate.
As a member of Third Act and the 1000 Grandmothers, I strongly urge the OCC to use its power to tell the Big Banks to divest in fossil fuels. Thank you.","The comment addresses Comptroller Hsu, expressing gratitude for addressing climate change in relation to banks. It criticizes banks for investing in fossil fuels despite public claims of addressing climate change, highlighting the risk to the financial system, marginalized communities, and the planet. The commenter supports proposed guidance urging banks to integrate climate risk management, plan for long-term climate impacts, define risk exposures, and align internal strategies with public commitments. They advocate for banks' climate risk management to influence supervisory ratings and call for strong guidance from the OCC to ensure banks' actions align with zero carbon emission commitments. The commenter, affiliated with Third Act and 1000 Grandmothers, urges the OCC to push banks to divest from fossil fuels."
